Newspeak3
'Root'
class AI_IDE_Support usingPlatform: platform ide: webIde aiAccess: aiAccessModule chatUI: chatUIModule = (
(*
 IDE module providing AI integration. Instantiates and exposes the
 general-purpose AIAccess and AIChatUI modules, and defines
 IDE-specific tools that allow an AI model to query the IDE via mirrors.

 This module follows the standard IDE module pattern: it is parameterized
 by the platform and the IDE, and is instantiated by HopscotchWebIDE.

 Other IDE presenters can access AI functionality through this module,
 e.g., to embed a ChatSubject in a method or class presenter.
*)
|
	(* IDE dependencies *)
	private Root = webIde namespacing Root.
	private systemScope = webIde namespacing systemScope.
	private ClassMirror = platform mirrors ClassMirror.
	private ObjectMirror = platform mirrors ObjectMirror.
	private ActivationMirror = platform mirrors ActivationMirror.
	private ClassDeclarationBuilder = platform mirrors ClassDeclarationBuilder.
	private List = platform collections List.
	private Map = platform collections Map.
	private ide = webIde.
	private retainedPlatform = platform.

	(* General-purpose AI modules *)
	public aiAccess = aiAccessModule.
	public chatUI = chatUIModule.

	(* Re-export commonly needed classes for use by other IDE modules *)
	public Tool = aiAccess Tool.
	public Provider = aiAccess Provider.
	public AnthropicProvider = aiAccess AnthropicProvider.
	public Session = aiAccess Session.
	private AIChatSetupSubject = chatUI AIChatSetupSubject.
	private AIChatSetupPresenter = chatUI AIChatSetupPresenter.
	private BaseChatSubject = chatUI ChatSubject.
	private BaseChatPresenter = chatUI ChatPresenter.

	(* --- AI focus state ---

	   Brain buttons in the IDE install a focus describing what the user is
	   currently asking the chat about. Three orthogonal pieces of state:

	   1. currentFocusBlock — a [ ^String ] block producing a description on
	      demand. Returned by the current_focus tool. A block (not a snapshot)
	      lets the description reflect live state — e.g. an in-progress
	      unaccepted edit, post-replacement updated source.

	   2. currentFocusValidator — a [ ^Boolean ] block that checks whether the
	      focused entity still exists. Run on every current_focus call. Returns
	      false (or raises) → focus is cleared. This catches all paths by which
	      an entity can disappear (explicit delete, add_or_replace_nested_class,
	      etc.) without each path needing to know about the focus.

	   3. focusKind / focusClassPath / focusSide / focusSelector — structured
	      identity used by isFocusedOnX:... matchers. Brain-button highlighting
	      compares against this rather than the Subject that installed the
	      focus. Reason: atomic install only forwards mixin objects, not
	      individual methods, so MethodMirror equality fails after a replace,
	      MirrorGroupSubject>>updateElements creates a fresh MethodSubject,
	      and any Subject-object-identity check fails. Structural matching
	      survives that. *)

	currentFocusBlock
	currentFocusValidator
	(* focusKind: #class | #classHeader | #method | #lazySlot | #evaluator | nil *)
	focusKind
	(* focusClassPath: String, dotted path *)
	focusClassPath
	(* focusSide: 'instance' | 'class' | nil *)
	focusSide
	(* focusSelector: Symbol — method or lazy-slot name, or nil *)
	focusSelector
	(* focusEvaluatorMirror_slot: ObjectMirror | ActivationMirror — set when
	   focusKind = #evaluator. Used directly as the identity for matcher
	   comparison; also exposed via the 'focus' object-registry id so
	   evaluate(in_id: 'focus') routes to the focused evaluator's receiver. *)
	focusEvaluatorMirror_slot

	(* focusEvaluatorSubject_slot: the EvaluatorSubject (or subclass) that
	   installed the focus. We retain it so 'focus' evaluations can append
	   results to its evaluator's results list, making them visible in the
	   IDE evaluator pane just like the workspace case. *)
	focusEvaluatorSubject_slot

	(* Single shared chat subject, lazily created on first use (e.g. when the
	   user clicks any brain button). Once created, all brain buttons reuse it
	   so the conversation continues as the user navigates. *)
	sharedChatSubject_slot

	(* AI-proposed code changes staged for atomic install. Keyed by
	   changeset id (e.g. "cs1"); the value is a List of change records
	   (Maps with kind, class_name, side, and either source or selector
	   plus old_source). Cleared on apply or discard. *)
	proposedChangesets = Map new.
	nextChangesetIdNum ::= 0.

	(* AI object registry — Map[String, ObjectMirror] of objects the AI
	   can refer to by id. Pre-populated with the AI workspace under id
	   'workspace' the first time it is reached. Subsequent entries come
	   from evaluate's non-primitive results, each auto-named (r1, r2, ...)
	   or AI-named via the name: parameter. Debugger activations get
	   their own ids (a1, a2, ...). Deliberately NOT cleared on chat-clear:
	   results reachable here may not be reachable from the workspace's
	   result list (e.g. when the AI navigates and evaluates transitively
	   through results). *)
	objectRegistry = Map new.
	nextResultIdNum ::= 0.
	nextActivationIdNum ::= 0.

	(* Cached AI workspace ObjectSubject. We keep the Subject (not just
	   the mirror) so workspace evaluations can be routed through the
	   subject's EvaluatorSubject — its evaluate: appends the resulting
	   ThreadMirror to the workspace's results list, which is what the
	   workspace presenter renders. Without this, the AI workspace UI
	   stays blank no matter how many evaluations run. *)
	aiWorkspaceSubject_slot

	(* Map[String, TestingInProgressSubject] keyed by test configuration
	   class simpleName. Captured by run_tests so subsequent
	   get_test_results / run_failing_tests / run_erroring_tests / run_test
	   tools can read and mutate the same Tester. Selective re-runs
	   operate on this cached Tester in place; a fresh run_tests
	   overwrites the entry. *)
	testersByConfigName = Map new.

	(* The chatHolder currently displaying the shared AI chat, paired
	   with the page subject it sits on. The brain-click path closes the
	   previous chat region ONLY when the new click is on the same page;
	   if the user navigates A → click → B → click → back to A, A's chat
	   region stays as the user left it. Set together via
	   activeChatHolder:page:. *)
	activeChatHolder_slot
	activeChatHolderPage_slot
|
) (

(* --- IDE-specific chat setup --- *)

public class IDEChatSetupSubject onModel: providerClass = AIChatSetupSubject onModel: providerClass (
(*
 Overrides session creation to include IDE-specific tools, and uses
 IDE-aware presenter and chat subject subclasses.
*)
) (

public createSession: provider = (
	| session |
	session:: Session provider: provider tools: tools.
	session systemPrompt: newspeakSystemPrompt.
	^session
)

public createPresenter = (
	^IDEChatSetupPresenter onSubject: self
)

public newChatSubjectFor: session = (
	| chat |
	chat:: IDEChatSubject onModel: session.
	(* Cache as the shared chat so subsequent brain clicks reuse this session. *)
	sharedChatSubject_slot:: chat.
	^chat
)

public isKindOfIDEChatSetupSubject = ( ^true )
isMyKind: other = ( ^other isKindOfIDEChatSetupSubject )

) : (
)

public class IDEChatSubject onModel: session = BaseChatSubject onModel: session (
(*
 IDE-aware chat subject; returns an IDE presenter so Inspect Presenter works.
*)
) (

public createPresenter = (
	^IDEChatPresenter onSubject: self
)

public isKindOfIDEChatSubject = ( ^true )
isMyKind: other = ( ^other isKindOfIDEChatSubject )

) : (
)

public class IDEChatSetupPresenter onSubject: s = AIChatSetupPresenter onSubject: s () (

respondToInspectPresenter = (
	enterSubject: (ide browsing ObjectSubject onModel: (ObjectMirror reflecting: self))
)

public isKindOfIDEChatSetupPresenter = ( ^true )
isMyKind: other = ( ^other isKindOfIDEChatSetupPresenter )

) : (
)

public class IDEChatPresenter onSubject: s = BaseChatPresenter onSubject: s () (

respondToInspectPresenter = (
	enterSubject: (ide browsing ObjectSubject onModel: (ObjectMirror reflecting: self))
)

public isKindOfIDEChatPresenter = ( ^true )
isMyKind: other = ( ^other isKindOfIDEChatPresenter )

) : (
)

(* --- Focus management ---

   A presenter signals what the user is asking about by installing a focus
   block. The chat does NOT push the focus into the conversation; it is pulled
   on demand via the current_focus tool. The block is re-evaluated on every
   pull, so live state (e.g. unaccepted edits) flows through automatically.
   To clear focus, pass nil. *)

(* Internal: install a description block and an existence validator.
   Brain buttons should call the kind-specific setXFocusOn: helpers below
   rather than this one; those also set the structured identity slots
   required by isFocusedOnX: matchers. *)
installFocusDescription: aBlock validator: aValidator = (
	currentFocusBlock:: aBlock.
	currentFocusValidator:: aValidator.
)

(* Kind-specific focus installers. Each sets:
   - the structured identity (focusKind, focusClassPath, focusSide,
     focusSelector) used by isFocusedOnX:... matchers for brain-button
     highlighting,
   - a description block returned by the current_focus AI tool,
   - an existence validator that re-checks the entity on every read. *)

public setClassFocusOn: cdm = (
	| qname |
	qname:: qualifiedNameOf: cdm.
	focusKind:: #class.
	focusClassPath:: qname.
	focusSide:: nil.
	focusSelector:: nil.
	installFocusDescription: ['Class: ', qname]
		validator: [classStillExists: cdm]
)

public setClassHeaderFocusOn: cdm = (
	| qname |
	qname:: qualifiedNameOf: cdm.
	focusKind:: #classHeader.
	focusClassPath:: qname.
	focusSide:: nil.
	focusSelector:: nil.
	installFocusDescription: ['Class header (factory + slots) of class ', qname]
		validator: [classStillExists: cdm]
)

public setMethodFocusOn: cdm side: side selector: sel = (
	| qname selSym |
	qname:: qualifiedNameOf: cdm.
	selSym:: sel asSymbol.
	focusKind:: #method.
	focusClassPath:: qname.
	focusSide:: side.
	focusSelector:: selSym.
	installFocusDescription: ['Method: ', qname, ' (', side, ' side) >> ', selSym asString]
		validator: [methodStillExists: cdm side: side selector: selSym]
)

public setLazySlotFocusOn: cdm side: side name: name = (
	| qname nameSym |
	qname:: qualifiedNameOf: cdm.
	nameSym:: name asSymbol.
	focusKind:: #lazySlot.
	focusClassPath:: qname.
	focusSide:: side.
	focusSelector:: nameSym.
	installFocusDescription: ['Lazy slot: ', qname, ' (', side, ' side) >> ', nameSym asString]
		validator: [lazySlotStillExists: cdm side: side name: nameSym]
)

public setTestRunFocusOn: configClass = (
	(* Focus on a test run for the given test configuration class.
	   The argument is the underlying Class object (not a mirror) — that's
	   what TestingInProgressSubject and TestingOutcomeSubject carry. *)
	| cdm qname |
	cdm:: (ClassMirror reflecting: configClass) mixin declaration.
	qname:: qualifiedNameOf: cdm.
	focusKind:: #testRun.
	focusClassPath:: qname.
	focusSide:: nil.
	focusSelector:: nil.
	installFocusDescription: ['Test results: ', qname]
		validator: [classStillExists: cdm]
)

public isFocusedOnTestRunClass: configClass ^ <Boolean> = (
	focusKind = #testRun ifFalse: [^false].
	^focusClassPath = (qualifiedNameOf: (ClassMirror reflecting: configClass) mixin declaration)
)

public setEvaluatorFocusOnSubject: evaluatorSubject = (
	(* Focus on an evaluator. evaluatorSubject is the EvaluatorSubject the
	   brain belongs to — it owns the mirror (the receiver of evaluations:
	   ObjectMirror for workspaces/inspectors, ActivationMirror for method
	   evaluators and debugger frames) AND the results list shown in the
	   IDE evaluator pane.
	   The 'focus' id in the object registry resolves dynamically to the
	   mirror, and evaluate's default in_id is 'focus' whenever evaluator
	   focus is active, so the AI's evaluations route through this receiver
	   without further configuration.
	   When the underlying mirror is an ActivationMirror (method evaluator,
	   lazy-slot evaluator, or debugger frame) we also register it as
	   an 'aN' so debugger tools can refer to it by id. *)
	| mirror |
	mirror:: evaluatorSubject model mirror.
	focusKind:: #evaluator.
	focusClassPath:: nil.
	focusSide:: nil.
	focusSelector:: nil.
	focusEvaluatorMirror_slot:: mirror.
	focusEvaluatorSubject_slot:: evaluatorSubject.
	(mirror isKindOfActivationMirror) ifTrue: [
		registerActivation: mirror
	].
	installFocusDescription: ['Evaluator (', (evaluatorDescription: mirror), ')']
		validator: [evaluatorMirrorStillValid: mirror]
)

evaluatorMirrorStillValid: mirror ^ <Boolean> = (
	(* For ActivationMirror, the activation must not have completed; once it
	   has, evaluating against it is meaningless. For ObjectMirror, the
	   reflectee stays alive as long as the mirror holds it, so we treat
	   it as always valid. *)
	^[
		(mirror isKindOfActivationMirror)
			ifTrue: [mirror isUncontinuable not]
			ifFalse: [true]
	] on: Error do: [:e | false]
)

evaluatorDescription: mirror ^ <String> = (
	^[
		(mirror isKindOfActivationMirror) ifTrue: [
			^'activation: ', ([mirror method name asString]
				on: Error do: [:e | '(unknown method)'])
		].
		'object: ', ([mirror getClass mixin name asString]
			on: Error do: [:e | '(unknown class)'])
	] on: Error do: [:e | 'unknown']
)

public isFocusedOnEvaluatorMirror: mirror ^ <Boolean> = (
	focusKind = #evaluator ifFalse: [^false].
	(* Use identity-aware mirror equality. ObjectMirror>>= and
	   ActivationMirror>>= both compare the underlying reflectee, which
	   is what we want. *)
	^focusEvaluatorMirror_slot = mirror
)

(* Structural matchers — brain buttons call these so highlighting tracks
   the focused entity (class path + side + selector) regardless of whether
   the Subject object survived atomic install. *)

public isFocusedOnClass: cdm ^ <Boolean> = (
	focusKind = #class ifFalse: [^false].
	^focusClassPath = (qualifiedNameOf: cdm)
)

public isFocusedOnClassHeader: cdm ^ <Boolean> = (
	focusKind = #classHeader ifFalse: [^false].
	^focusClassPath = (qualifiedNameOf: cdm)
)

public isFocusedOnMethod: cdm side: side selector: sel ^ <Boolean> = (
	focusKind = #method ifFalse: [^false].
	focusClassPath = (qualifiedNameOf: cdm) ifFalse: [^false].
	focusSide = side ifFalse: [^false].
	^focusSelector = sel asSymbol
)

public isFocusedOnLazySlot: cdm side: side name: name ^ <Boolean> = (
	focusKind = #lazySlot ifFalse: [^false].
	focusClassPath = (qualifiedNameOf: cdm) ifFalse: [^false].
	focusSide = side ifFalse: [^false].
	^focusSelector = name asSymbol
)

(* Existence checks used by the structured focus validators. Each resolves
   the qualified class path freshly through the namespace and compares via
   ClassDeclarationMirror>>= (which compares the underlying mixins). After
   atomic-install instance forwarding, a replaced class's old mirror and a
   freshly-resolved mirror compare equal because both reach the same
   (forwarded) mixin. Deletions cause resolveClassPath: to raise; the
   on:Error handler returns false. *)

public classStillExists: cdm ^ <Boolean> = (
	^[(resolveClassPath: (qualifiedNameOf: cdm)) = cdm]
		on: Error do: [:e | false]
)

public methodStillExists: cdm side: side selector: sel ^ <Boolean> = (
	^[
		| resolved mixin |
		resolved:: resolveClassPath: (qualifiedNameOf: cdm).
		resolved = cdm
			and: [
				mixin:: side = 'class'
					ifTrue: [resolved classSide]
					ifFalse: [resolved instanceSide].
				(findMethodMirrorNamed: sel inMixin: mixin) isNil not
			]
	] on: Error do: [:e | false]
)

public lazySlotStillExists: cdm side: side name: name ^ <Boolean> = (
	^[
		| resolved mixin |
		resolved:: resolveClassPath: (qualifiedNameOf: cdm).
		resolved = cdm
			and: [
				mixin:: side = 'class'
					ifTrue: [resolved classSide]
					ifFalse: [resolved instanceSide].
				(findLazySlotMirrorNamed: name inMixin: mixin) isNil not
			]
	] on: Error do: [:e | false]
)

public clearFocus = (
	currentFocusBlock:: nil.
	currentFocusValidator:: nil.
	focusKind:: nil.
	focusClassPath:: nil.
	focusSide:: nil.
	focusSelector:: nil.
	focusEvaluatorMirror_slot:: nil.
	focusEvaluatorSubject_slot:: nil.
)

(* --- Active chat region tracking ---

   Brain buttons drop the shared chat into their presenter's chatHolder.
   Without coordination, clicking a different brain leaves the previous
   chatHolder still displaying the chat, so multiple chat regions appear
   on screen at once. We track the most recently-activated chatHolder so
   the brain-click path can close it before activating a new one.

   Tracking is intentionally scoped to brain-click actions only — not
   to updateVisualsFromSameKind:'s re-render restore path, which must
   not close anything. The actual clearing (which needs Hopscotch's
   `nothing` fragment) happens in the Browsing-side brain action; we
   just hold the reference. *)

public activeChatHolder = (
	^activeChatHolder_slot
)

public activeChatHolderPage = (
	^activeChatHolderPage_slot
)

public activeChatHolder: aChatHolder page: aPageSubject = (
	activeChatHolder_slot:: aChatHolder.
	activeChatHolderPage_slot:: aPageSubject.
)

public currentFocusDescription ^ <String> = (
	currentFocusBlock isNil ifTrue: [^'(no focus set)'].
	(* Validate first: if the focused entity no longer exists (because a
	   changeset deleted or replaced its enclosing class etc.), drop the
	   focus instead of returning stale text. *)
	currentFocusValidator isNil ifFalse: [
		([currentFocusValidator value] on: Error do: [:e | false]) ifFalse: [
			clearFocus.
			^'(no focus set)'
		]
	].
	^[currentFocusBlock value]
		on: Error
		do: [:e | '(focus block raised: ', e messageText, ')']
)

(* Entry point for the toolbar brain button: if the user has already saved an
   API key for the Anthropic provider, go straight to a chat; otherwise return
   the setup subject so the user can enter a key. *)
public chatLauncher = (
	^ensureSharedChat
)

(* Return the cached shared chat subject, or — if no chat has been created yet
   — a setup subject the caller can navigate to so the user can enter a key.
   The setup subject's startChat caches the resulting chat in sharedChatSubject_slot. *)
public ensureSharedChat = (
	| setup chat |
	sharedChatSubject_slot isNil ifFalse: [^sharedChatSubject_slot].
	setup:: IDEChatSetupSubject onModel: AnthropicProvider.
	setup apiKey isEmpty ifTrue: [^setup].
	chat:: setup startChat.
	chat isNil ifTrue: [^setup].
	(* startChat goes through newChatSubjectFor:, which has already cached. *)
	^sharedChatSubject_slot
)

(* --- Class lookup helpers --- *)

classDeclarationNamed: name <String> ^ <ClassDeclarationMirror> = (
	| cls |
	cls:: Root at: name asSymbol ifAbsent: [
		Error signal: 'Class not found: ', name
	].
	cls isKindOfBehavior ifFalse: [
		Error signal: 'Not a class: ', name
	].
	^(ClassMirror reflecting: cls) mixin declaration
)

resolveNamespacePath: path <String> ^ <Object> = (
	(* Navigate the namespace tree starting at Root. A leading 'Root.' segment
	   is optional. Returns the entry (which may be a Namespace, a class, a
	   Document, an Image, etc.). Signals an error if a segment is not found. *)
	| parts start current |
	parts:: path isEmpty ifTrue: [{}] ifFalse: [path findTokens: '.'].
	current:: Root.
	start:: (parts isEmpty not and: [(parts at: 1) = 'Root'])
		ifTrue: [2] ifFalse: [1].
	start to: parts size do: [:i |
		| seg = parts at: i. |
		current:: current at: seg asSymbol ifAbsent: [
			Error signal: 'Not found in namespace path: ', seg
		].
	].
	^current
)

kindOf: value <Object> ^ <String> = (
	value isKindOfNamespace ifTrue: [^'namespace'].
	value isKindOfBehavior ifTrue: [^'class'].
	value isKindOfDocument ifTrue: [^'document'].
	value isKindOfString ifTrue: [^'string'].
	value isKindOfJSAlien ifTrue: [
		('IMG' = (value at: 'nodeName')) ifTrue: [^'image'].
		^'alien'
	].
	^'other'
)

public qualifiedNameOf: cdm <ClassDeclarationMirror> ^ <String> = (
	(* Walks the enclosing-class chain to produce a dotted path,
	   e.g. "RuntimeForHopscotchForHTML.Platform.Images". *)
	| path enclosing |
	path:: cdm simpleName.
	enclosing:: cdm enclosingClass.
	[enclosing isNil] whileFalse: [
		path:: enclosing simpleName, '.', path.
		enclosing:: enclosing enclosingClass.
	].
	^path
)

resolveClassPath: path <String> ^ <ClassDeclarationMirror> = (
	| parts cdm |
	parts:: path findTokens: '.'.
	cdm:: classDeclarationNamed: (parts at: 1).
	2 to: parts size do: [:i |
		| nestedName found |
		nestedName:: (parts at: i) asSymbol.
		found:: false.
		cdm instanceSide nestedClasses do: [:nc |
			nc simpleName = nestedName ifTrue: [
				cdm:: nc.
				found:: true.
			].
		].
		found ifFalse: [
			Error signal: 'Nested class not found: ', (parts at: i),
				' in ', cdm simpleName
		].
	].
	^cdm
)

namespaceSubjectForPath: path <String> ^ <Object> = (
	(* Build a NamespaceSubject for the namespace at the given dotted path,
	   or for Root if the path is empty or 'Root'. Raises an error if the
	   path resolves to something that is not a Namespace. *)
	| parts ns key |
	(path isEmpty or: [path = 'Root']) ifTrue: [
		^ide browsing NamespaceSubject new
	].
	ns:: resolveNamespacePath: path.
	ns isKindOfNamespace ifFalse: [
		Error signal: path, ' is not a namespace (it is a ', (kindOf: ns), ')'
	].
	parts:: path findTokens: '.'.
	key:: (parts at: parts size) asSymbol.
	^ide browsing NamespaceSubject onModel: ns key: key
)

formatAccess: am ^ <String> = (
	am = #public ifTrue: [^'public '].
	am = #private ifTrue: [^'private '].
	^''
)

(* --- Proposed-changeset helpers --- *)

freshChangesetId ^ <String> = (
	nextChangesetIdNum:: nextChangesetIdNum + 1.
	^'cs', nextChangesetIdNum printString
)

mixinForChange: change ^ <Object> = (
	| cdm side |
	cdm:: resolveClassPath: (change at: 'class_name').
	side:: (change includesKey: 'side')
		ifTrue: [change at: 'side']
		ifFalse: ['instance'].
	^side = 'class' ifTrue: [cdm classSide] ifFalse: [cdm instanceSide]
)

findMethodMirrorNamed: selector <Symbol> inMixin: mixin ^ <Object> = (
	mixin methods do: [:mm | mm name = selector ifTrue: [^mm]].
	^nil
)

findLazySlotMirrorNamed: selector <Symbol> inMixin: mixin ^ <Object> = (
	mixin lazySlots do: [:ls | ls name = selector ifTrue: [^ls]].
	^nil
)

isMemberKind: kind ^ <Boolean> = (
	^kind = 'add_or_replace_method'
		or: [kind = 'delete_method'
		or: [kind = 'add_or_replace_lazy_slot'
		or: [kind = 'delete_lazy_slot']]]
)

validateChange: change ^ <Object> = (
	(* Returns a Map record of the validated change. Raises if invalid. *)
	| kind record |
	kind:: change at: 'kind'.
	record:: Map new.
	record at: 'kind' put: kind.
	record at: 'class_name' put: (change at: 'class_name').
	(isMemberKind: kind) ifTrue: [
		| side mixin sel old |
		side:: (change includesKey: 'side') ifTrue: [change at: 'side'] ifFalse: ['instance'].
		(side = 'instance' or: [side = 'class']) ifFalse: [
			Error signal: 'side must be "instance" or "class", got: ', side
		].
		record at: 'side' put: side.
		mixin:: mixinForChange: change.
		kind = 'add_or_replace_method' ifTrue: [
			record at: 'source' put: (change at: 'source'). ^record
		].
		kind = 'add_or_replace_lazy_slot' ifTrue: [
			record at: 'source' put: (change at: 'source'). ^record
		].
		kind = 'delete_method' ifTrue: [
			sel:: (change at: 'selector') asSymbol.
			record at: 'selector' put: sel.
			old:: findMethodMirrorNamed: sel inMixin: mixin.
			old isNil ifTrue: [
				Error signal: 'No method ', sel, ' on the ', side, ' side of ',
					(record at: 'class_name')
			].
			record at: 'old_source' put: old source.
			^record
		].
		kind = 'delete_lazy_slot' ifTrue: [
			sel:: (change at: 'selector') asSymbol.
			record at: 'selector' put: sel.
			old:: findLazySlotMirrorNamed: sel inMixin: mixin.
			old isNil ifTrue: [
				Error signal: 'No lazy slot ', sel, ' on the ', side, ' side of ',
					(record at: 'class_name')
			].
			record at: 'old_source' put: old source.
			^record
		].
	].
	kind = 'set_class_header' ifTrue: [
		| cdm |
		record at: 'source' put: (change at: 'source').
		cdm:: resolveClassPath: (record at: 'class_name').
		record at: 'old_source' put: cdm header source.
		^record
	].
	kind = 'add_or_replace_nested_class' ifTrue: [
		(* class_name is the enclosing class (must already exist). *)
		record at: 'source' put: (change at: 'source').
		resolveClassPath: (record at: 'class_name').
		^record
	].
	kind = 'delete_nested_class' ifTrue: [
		| segments cdm |
		segments:: (record at: 'class_name') findTokens: '.'.
		segments size < 2 ifTrue: [
			Error signal: 'delete_nested_class requires a nested class path (got top-level: ',
				(record at: 'class_name'),
				'). Top-level deletion is not supported by this tool.'
		].
		cdm:: resolveClassPath: (record at: 'class_name').
		record at: 'old_source' put: cdm source.
		^record
	].
	kind = 'add_top_level_class' ifTrue: [
		| name existing |
		record at: 'source' put: (change at: 'source').
		name:: change at: 'class_name'.
		existing:: Root at: name asSymbol ifAbsent: [nil].
		existing isNil ifFalse: [
			Error signal: 'A top-level entry named ', name, ' already exists in Root'
		].
		^record
	].
	Error signal: 'Unknown change kind: ', kind
)

formatChangesetId: id records: records ^ <String> = (
	| result count |
	count:: records size.
	result:: 'Changeset ', id, ' (', count printString,
		(count = 1 ifTrue: [' change):'] ifFalse: [' changes):']), '\n'.
	records do: [:r |
		| kind sideStr |
		kind:: r at: 'kind'.
		sideStr:: (r includesKey: 'side')
			ifTrue: [' (', (r at: 'side'), ' side)']
			ifFalse: [''].
		result:: result, '\n[', kind, '] ', (r at: 'class_name'), sideStr.
		(kind = 'delete_method' or: [kind = 'delete_lazy_slot']) ifTrue: [
			result:: result, ' >> ', (r at: 'selector') asString, '\n',
				'--- removing\n', (r at: 'old_source'), '\n'.
		] ifFalse: [
			kind = 'set_class_header' ifTrue: [
				result:: result, '\n--- old header\n', (r at: 'old_source'), '\n',
					'+++ new header\n', (r at: 'source'), '\n'.
			] ifFalse: [
				kind = 'delete_nested_class' ifTrue: [
					result:: result, '\n--- removing class\n', (r at: 'old_source'), '\n'.
				] ifFalse: [
					(* add_or_replace_method, add_or_replace_lazy_slot,
					   add_or_replace_nested_class, add_top_level_class *)
					result:: result, '\n+++ new source\n', (r at: 'source'), '\n'.
				]
			]
		].
	].
	result:: result, '\nWhen the user approves, call apply_changeset with id "', id, '".'.
	^result
)

intermediateOf: builder = (
	(* Reach into a {Class,Mixin}Builder's private 'intermediate' slot.
	   AtomicInstallWrapper>>install:into: uses the same trick. *)
	^((ObjectMirror reflecting: builder) getSlot: #intermediate) reflectee
)

patchEnclosingOf: childClassBuilder withParent: parentClassBuilder = (
	(* When we navigate DOWN from a top-level builder into
	   instanceSide.nestedClasses, the nested IR's enclosingClass is the
	   parent IntermediateClassDeclaration (set in buildIntermediate:from:within:).
	   But ClassDeclarationBuilder>>enclosingClass expects an IntermediateMixin
	   (the parent's instance-side mixin) — see the patch at line 572 of
	   MirrorsForPrimordialSoup.ns, which only runs on the mirror-up path.
	   Mirror that patch here so the compiler can walk the scope chain. *)
	| childIR parentInstanceSideIR |
	childIR:: intermediateOf: childClassBuilder.
	parentInstanceSideIR:: intermediateOf: parentClassBuilder instanceSide.
	childIR enclosingClass: parentInstanceSideIR.
)

navigateToBuilderForSegments: segments <Array> withBuilderMap: builderByTopLevel ^ <Object> = (
	(* Resolve a dotted class path (given as segments) to a ClassDeclarationBuilder.
	   For top-level segments, fetch or create the cached top-level builder.
	   For nested segments, walk DOWN inside it, patching enclosingClass linkages
	   as we go (see patchEnclosingOf:withParent: for why). *)
	| topName targetClassBuilder |
	topName:: segments at: 1.
	targetClassBuilder:: builderByTopLevel at: topName ifAbsent: [
		| topCdm topBuilder |
		topCdm:: classDeclarationNamed: topName.
		topBuilder:: topCdm asBuilder.
		builderByTopLevel at: topName put: topBuilder.
		topBuilder
	].
	2 to: segments size do: [:i |
		| seg found |
		seg:: segments at: i.
		found:: nil.
		targetClassBuilder instanceSide nestedClasses do: [:ncBuilder |
			ncBuilder name = seg ifTrue: [found:: ncBuilder]
		].
		found isNil ifTrue: [
			Error signal: 'Nested class not found in builder tree: ', seg,
				' (under ', topName, ')'
		].
		patchEnclosingOf: found withParent: targetClassBuilder.
		targetClassBuilder:: found
	].
	^targetClassBuilder
)

applyOneRecord: r withBuilderMap: builderByTopLevel = (
	| kind segments targetClassBuilder side mixinBuilder |
	kind:: r at: 'kind'.
	kind = 'add_top_level_class' ifTrue: [
		| newBuilder name |
		newBuilder:: ClassDeclarationBuilder fromSource: (r at: 'source').
		name:: newBuilder name asSymbol.
		(builderByTopLevel includesKey: name) ifTrue: [
			Error signal: 'Top-level builder for ', name,
				' already present in this changeset (duplicate add or conflict)'
		].
		builderByTopLevel at: name put: newBuilder.
		^self
	].
	kind = 'delete_nested_class' ifTrue: [
		| parentBuilder targetName |
		segments:: (r at: 'class_name') findTokens: '.'.
		parentBuilder:: navigateToBuilderForSegments: (segments copyFrom: 1 to: segments size - 1)
			withBuilderMap: builderByTopLevel.
		targetName:: (segments at: segments size) asSymbol.
		parentBuilder instanceSide nestedClasses removeMirrorNamed: targetName.
		^self
	].
	(* All remaining kinds operate on a target class identified by class_name. *)
	segments:: (r at: 'class_name') findTokens: '.'.
	targetClassBuilder:: navigateToBuilderForSegments: segments
		withBuilderMap: builderByTopLevel.
	kind = 'set_class_header' ifTrue: [
		^targetClassBuilder header source: (r at: 'source')
	].
	kind = 'add_or_replace_nested_class' ifTrue: [
		^targetClassBuilder instanceSide nestedClasses addFromSource: (r at: 'source')
	].
	(* Member-level kinds: route through instance or class side. *)
	side:: r at: 'side'.
	mixinBuilder:: side = 'class'
		ifTrue: [targetClassBuilder classSide]
		ifFalse: [targetClassBuilder instanceSide].
	kind = 'add_or_replace_method' ifTrue: [
		^mixinBuilder methods addFromSource: (r at: 'source')
	].
	kind = 'delete_method' ifTrue: [
		^mixinBuilder methods removeMirrorNamed: (r at: 'selector')
	].
	kind = 'add_or_replace_lazy_slot' ifTrue: [
		^mixinBuilder lazySlots addFromSource: (r at: 'source')
	].
	kind = 'delete_lazy_slot' ifTrue: [
		^mixinBuilder lazySlots removeMirrorNamed: (r at: 'selector')
	].
	Error signal: 'Unknown change kind in apply: ', kind
)

applyChangesetRecords: records = (
	(* Aggregates changes per top-level class and installs them as one
	   atomic transaction via the platform's atomic installer. *)
	| builderByTopLevel builders newTopLevelNames mixins |
	builderByTopLevel:: Map new.
	newTopLevelNames:: List new.
	records do: [:r |
		(r at: 'kind') = 'add_top_level_class' ifTrue: [
			newTopLevelNames add: (r at: 'class_name')
		].
		applyOneRecord: r withBuilderMap: builderByTopLevel
	].
	builders:: List new.
	builderByTopLevel keysAndValuesDo: [:k :v | builders add: v].
	mixins:: ide installFromBuilders: builders.
	(* The atomic installer returns mirrors but does NOT add new top-level
	   classes to the IDE namespace on primordialsoup (the JS mirror builders
	   do; the wasm ones don't). Mirror the IDE's own post-install step. *)
	mixins do: [:m |
		(newTopLevelNames includes: m name) ifTrue: [
			Root at: m name asSymbol put: m declaration applyToObject reflectee
		]
	].
)

(* --- Object registry / evaluation helpers --- *)

aiWorkspaceSubject ^ <Object> = (
	(* Get-or-create the AI workspace via the WorkspaceManager's standard
	   API. The workspace state (the workspaces list, counters) is in the
	   WorkspaceManager module instance; the methods that manipulate it
	   (addWorkspace, getWorkspace:, ...) are on the nested
	   AllWorkspacesSubject class, accessing module state via lexical
	   scope. Browsing.ns uses the same idiom — create a fresh
	   AllWorkspacesSubject and call getWorkspace: on it; all subject
	   instances share the same enclosing workspaces list, so the lookup-
	   or-create is global to the IDE session.
	   The resulting workspace is registered in the manager's list and
	   inherits Workspace's platform/ide/Root bindings. Cached so its
	   evaluator (which owns the visible-in-UI results list) is the same
	   one each call. *)
	aiWorkspaceSubject_slot isNil ifFalse: [^aiWorkspaceSubject_slot].
	aiWorkspaceSubject_slot::
		ide theWorkspaceManager AllWorkspacesSubject new
			getWorkspace: 'AIWorkspace'.
	objectRegistry at: 'workspace' put: aiWorkspaceSubject_slot objectMirror.
	^aiWorkspaceSubject_slot
)

aiWorkspaceMirror ^ <Object> = (
	^aiWorkspaceSubject objectMirror
)

registerResult: aMirror <Object> withName: nameOrNil <String | Nil> ^ <String> = (
	| id |
	(nameOrNil isNil or: [nameOrNil isEmpty]) ifTrue: [
		nextResultIdNum:: nextResultIdNum + 1.
		id:: 'r', nextResultIdNum printString
	] ifFalse: [
		id:: nameOrNil
	].
	objectRegistry at: id put: aMirror.
	^id
)

registerActivation: anActivationMirror <Object> ^ <String> = (
	(* Register an ActivationMirror under an 'aN' id, deduping against
	   already-registered activations (ActivationMirror>>= compares
	   underlying activation identity, so the same frame stays under one
	   id no matter how many times it's reached). *)
	| id |
	objectRegistry keysAndValuesDo: [:k :v |
		((k size > 0 and: [(k at: 1) = 'a' first])
			and: [v = anActivationMirror]) ifTrue: [^k]
	].
	nextActivationIdNum:: nextActivationIdNum + 1.
	id:: 'a', nextActivationIdNum printString.
	objectRegistry at: id put: anActivationMirror.
	^id
)

activationForId: id <String> ^ <Object> = (
	| m |
	m:: mirrorForObjectId: id.
	m isKindOfActivationMirror ifFalse: [
		Error signal: 'Object [', id, '] is not an activation frame'
	].
	^m
)

isPrimitiveResult: aMirror <Object> ^ <Boolean> = (
	(* Primitives (Integer, Float, String, Symbol, Boolean, Character, nil)
	   are NOT registered — the AI can use their printString directly. *)
	| r |
	r:: aMirror reflectee.
	r isNil ifTrue: [^true].
	r isKindOfInteger ifTrue: [^true].
	r isKindOfFloat ifTrue: [^true].
	r isKindOfString ifTrue: [^true].
	r isKindOfSymbol ifTrue: [^true].
	r isKindOfBoolean ifTrue: [^true].
	r isKindOfCharacter ifTrue: [^true].
	^false
)

summaryOf: aMirror <Object> ^ <String> = (
	| className printStr |
	className:: [aMirror getClass mixin name asString]
		on: Error do: [:e | '(class?)'].
	printStr:: [aMirror reflectee printString]
		on: Error do: [:e | '(printString raised: ', e messageText, ')'].
	printStr size > 200 ifTrue: [printStr:: (printStr copyFrom: 1 to: 197), '...'].
	^className, ': ', printStr
)

mirrorForObjectId: id <String> ^ <Object> = (
	id = 'workspace' ifTrue: [^aiWorkspaceMirror].
	id = 'focus' ifTrue: [
		(* Resolves dynamically to whichever evaluator the user has focused
		   on, so the AI never has to track a stale id between turns. *)
		focusKind = #evaluator ifFalse: [
			Error signal:
				'No evaluator focus is set. Click a brain on a workspace, ' ,
				'object inspector, method evaluator, or debugger activation, ' ,
				'or pass in_id: "workspace" to use the AI workspace.'
		].
		^focusEvaluatorMirror_slot
	].
	^objectRegistry at: id ifAbsent: [
		Error signal: 'No such object id: ', id,
			'. Use list_objects to see registered ids.'
	]
)

(* --- IDE tool definitions --- *)

public tools ^ <List> = (
	^{
		getClassSourceTool.
		getMemberSourceTool.
		getClassHeaderTool.
		listClassMembersTool.
		sendersTool.
		implementorsTool.
		searchClassesTool.
		listNamespaceTool.
		getDocumentTool.
		createDocumentTool.
		setDocumentContentsTool.
		deleteDocumentTool.
		listAmpletsTool.
		addAmpletTool.
		setAmpletExpressionTool.
		deleteAmpletTool.
		listMediaTool.
		deleteMediaTool.
		webFetchTool.
		currentFocusTool.
		navigateToClassTool.
		navigateToNamespaceTool.
		navigateToDocumentTool.
		showTestsTool.
		runTestsTool.
		getTestResultsTool.
		getTestFailureDetailsTool.
		runFailingTestsTool.
		runErroringTestsTool.
		runOneTestTool.
		proposeChangesTool.
		applyChangesetTool.
		evaluateTool.
		navigateToObjectTool.
		inspectObjectTool.
		listObjectsTool.
		forgetObjectTool.
		getCurrentFrameTool.
		getStackTraceTool.
		getCurrentExpressionTool.
		inspectActivationTool.
		stepTool.
		returnFromTool.
		continueThreadTool.
	}
)

getClassSourceTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_class_source'
		description: 'Get the full source code of a Newspeak class. Use a dotted path for nested classes (e.g. "ShapeLibrary.Circle").'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Class name or dotted path (e.g. MyClass or Outer.Inner)"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			(resolveClassPath: (input at: 'class_name')) source
		]
)

getMemberSourceTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_member_source'
		description: 'Get the source of a method or a lazy slot in a class. Specify the selector (the member''s name) including colons for keyword methods (e.g. "at:put:"). Searches the named class side''s methods first, then its lazy slots. For ordinary (non-lazy) slot declarations, use get_class_header.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Class name or dotted path"},"selector":{"type":"string","description":"Method or lazy-slot name (e.g. foo, at:put:, +)"},"side":{"type":"string","enum":["instance","class"],"description":"Which side of the class (default: instance)"}},"required":["class_name","selector"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| cdm mixin selector found result |
			cdm:: resolveClassPath: (input at: 'class_name').
			selector:: (input at: 'selector') asSymbol.
			mixin:: ((input at: 'side') = 'class')
				ifTrue: [cdm classSide]
				ifFalse: [cdm instanceSide].
			found:: false.
			result:: ''.
			mixin methods do: [:mm |
				mm name = selector ifTrue: [
					result:: mm source.
					found:: true.
				].
			].
			found ifFalse: [
				mixin lazySlots do: [:ls |
					ls name = selector ifTrue: [
						result:: ls source.
						found:: true.
					].
				].
			].
			found ifFalse: [
				Error signal: 'No method or lazy slot named ', selector,
					' in ', cdm simpleName
			].
			result
		]
)

getClassHeaderTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_class_header'
		description: 'Get just the class header (factory method signature, superclass clause, slot declarations) without the method bodies.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			(resolveClassPath: (input at: 'class_name')) header source
		]
)

listClassMembersTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'list_class_members'
		description: 'List all members (methods, slots, nested classes, lazy slots) of a class with their access modifiers. Does not include source code - use get_member_source for that.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| cdm result |
			cdm:: resolveClassPath: (input at: 'class_name').
			result:: 'Class: ', cdm simpleName, '\n'.
			result:: result, 'Factory: ', cdm primaryFactorySelector, '\n'.

			result:: result, '\nSlots:\n'.
			cdm instanceSide slots do: [:sm |
				result:: result, '  ', (formatAccess: sm accessModifier),
					sm name,
					(sm isMutable ifTrue: [' (mutable)'] ifFalse: [' (immutable)']),
					'\n'.
			].

			result:: result, '\nInstance methods:\n'.
			cdm instanceSide methods do: [:mm |
				result:: result, '  ', (formatAccess: mm accessModifier),
					mm name, '\n'.
			].

			cdm instanceSide lazySlots do: [:ls |
				result:: result, '  ',
					(formatAccess: ls accessModifier),
					'lazy ', ls name, '\n'.
			].

			result:: result, '\nClass methods:\n'.
			cdm classSide methods do: [:mm |
				result:: result, '  ', (formatAccess: mm accessModifier),
					mm name, '\n'.
			].

			result:: result, '\nNested classes:\n'.
			cdm instanceSide nestedClasses do: [:nc |
				result:: result, '  ', (formatAccess: nc accessModifier),
					nc simpleName, '\n'.
			].

			result
		]
)

sendersTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'senders_of'
		description: 'Find all methods that send a given message selector. Returns the defining class and method for each sender.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"selector":{"type":"string","description":"The message selector to search for (e.g. add:, printString, +)"}},"required":["selector"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| selector result count |
			selector:: (input at: 'selector') asSymbol.
			result:: 'Senders of #', selector, ':\n'.
			count:: 0.
			systemScope sendersOf: selector do: [:mirror |
				count:: count + 1.
				mirror isKindOfMethodMirror ifTrue: [
					result:: result, '  ',
						(qualifiedNameOf: mirror definingMixin declaration), ' >> ',
						mirror name, '\n'.
				] ifFalse: [
					mirror isKindOfLazySlotMirror ifTrue: [
						result:: result, '  ',
							(qualifiedNameOf: mirror definingMixin declaration), ' >> ',
							mirror name, ' (lazy slot)\n'.
					] ifFalse: [
						mirror isKindOfClassDeclarationMirror ifTrue: [
							result:: result, '  ',
								(qualifiedNameOf: mirror), ' (class header)\n'.
						]
					]
				]
			].
			count = 0 ifTrue: [
				result:: result, '  (none found)\n'.
			].
			result
		]
)

implementorsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'implementors_of'
		description: 'Find all classes that implement a given message selector. Returns the defining class and access modifier for each implementor.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"selector":{"type":"string","description":"The message selector to search for"}},"required":["selector"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| selector result count |
			selector:: (input at: 'selector') asSymbol.
			result:: 'Implementors of #', selector, ':\n'.
			count:: 0.
			systemScope implementorsOf: selector do: [:mirror |
				count:: count + 1.
				mirror isKindOfLazySlotMirror ifTrue: [
					result:: result, '  ',
						(formatAccess: mirror accessModifier),
						(qualifiedNameOf: mirror definingMixin declaration), ' >> ',
						mirror name, ' (lazy slot)\n'.
				].
				mirror isKindOfMethodMirror ifTrue: [
					result:: result, '  ',
						(formatAccess: mirror accessModifier),
						(qualifiedNameOf: mirror definingMixin declaration), ' >> ',
						mirror name, '\n'.
				].
				mirror isKindOfClassDeclarationMirror ifTrue: [
					result:: result, '  ',
						(qualifiedNameOf: mirror), ' (class/slot)\n'.
				].
			].
			count = 0 ifTrue: [
				result:: result, '  (none found)\n'.
			].
			result
		]
)

listNamespaceTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'list_namespace'
		description: 'List the entries of a Newspeak namespace. With no argument (or an empty path), lists the IDE Root namespace. Use a dotted path to drill into a nested namespace (e.g. "Icons" or "Root.Icons"). Each entry is reported as "name (kind)" where kind is one of: namespace, class, document, string, image, alien, other.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"path":{"type":"string","description":"Optional dotted path to a namespace. Empty or omitted means Root."}}}'
		handler: [:input |
			| path ns label result |
			(* input is a JS Alien — use includesKey: rather than at:ifAbsent:,
			   which the alien does not understand. *)
			path:: (input includesKey: 'path')
				ifTrue: [input at: 'path']
				ifFalse: [''].
			ns:: resolveNamespacePath: path.
			label:: path isEmpty ifTrue: ['Root'] ifFalse: [path].
			result:: 'Namespace ', label, ':\n'.
			ns keysAndValuesDo: [:k :v |
				result:: result, '  ', k, ' (', (kindOf: v), ')\n'.
			].
			result
		]
)

currentFocusTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'current_focus'
		description: 'Return a description of what the user is currently asking about in the IDE — the class, method, namespace, document or other entity they pointed the chat at, plus any in-progress (unaccepted) edits if relevant. Returns "(no focus set)" if the user has not indicated a focus. Call this first whenever the user refers to "this", "here", or names a member without a class, before guessing.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{}}'
		handler: [:input |
			currentFocusDescription
		]
)

webFetchTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'web_fetch'
		description: 'Fetch a URL and return its response body as text. Useful for consulting the published Newspeak language specification and grammar (https://newspeaklanguage.org/spec/newspeak-spec.tex) or the tutorial (https://newspeaklanguage.org/pubs/newspeak-2025-tutorial.pdf), and for other web lookups. The response is returned as a single string; for binary content (PDFs, images) the text decoding may be lossy.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"url":{"type":"string","description":"Absolute URL to fetch (https:// or http://)."}},"required":["url"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			aiAccess webFetch: (input at: 'url')
		]
)

(* --- Document management helpers --- *)

parentNamespaceAndLeaf: dottedPath <String> ^ <Object> = (
	(* Walk the path segments to the parent namespace; return a 2-tuple
	   {parentNamespace. leafName}. Used by create/delete to locate the
	   container of the entry being added/removed. Raises if any
	   intermediate segment isn't found or isn't a namespace. *)
	| parts current i leaf |
	parts:: dottedPath findTokens: '.'.
	parts isEmpty ifTrue: [
		Error signal: 'Empty path'
	].
	leaf:: parts at: parts size.
	current:: Root.
	i:: 1.
	(parts isEmpty not and: [(parts at: 1) = 'Root']) ifTrue: [i:: 2].
	[i < parts size] whileTrue: [
		| seg = parts at: i. |
		current:: current at: seg asSymbol ifAbsent: [
			Error signal: 'Namespace segment not found: ', seg
		].
		current isKindOfNamespace ifFalse: [
			Error signal: 'Path segment is not a namespace: ', seg
		].
		i:: i + 1
	].
	^{current. leaf}
)

documentAt: dottedPath <String> ^ <Object> = (
	| entry |
	entry:: resolveNamespacePath: dottedPath.
	entry isKindOfDocument ifFalse: [
		Error signal: 'Not a document: ', dottedPath,
			' (it is a ', (kindOf: entry), ')'
	].
	^entry
)

(* Parse a document's contents HTML into a detached div whose innerHTML
   holds it. Manipulate the div via DOM methods, then read innerHTML back
   to produce the updated contents. Same round-trip the IDE uses in
   Documents.ns freshDocumentFromDOM:. *)
parseAmpletContainer: html <String> ^ <Object> = (
	| jsDoc div |
	jsDoc:: retainedPlatform js global at: 'document'.
	div:: jsDoc createElement: 'div'.
	div at: 'innerHTML' put: html.
	^div
)

(* Locate the amplet element whose ampletId attribute equals id. Raises
   if none is found. *)
findAmpletWithId: id <String> in: container <Object> ^ <Object> = (
	| amplets count i |
	amplets:: container getElementsByClassName: 'ampleforth'.
	count:: amplets at: 'length'.
	i:: 0.
	[i < count] whileTrue: [
		| amplet thisId |
		amplet:: amplets at: i.
		thisId:: amplet getAttribute: 'ampletId'.
		thisId = id ifTrue: [^amplet].
		i:: i + 1
	].
	Error signal: 'No amplet with ampletId="', id, '" in this document'
)

createDocumentTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'create_document'
		description: 'Create a new Ampleforth document at the given dotted path. The path''s parent must be an existing namespace (e.g. just "MyNotes" puts it in Root; "Foo.Bar.Notes" puts Notes in Root.Foo.Bar). Optional initial_contents is the document''s starting HTML; if omitted, the document is created with the default blank template. Fails if any entry already exists at that path.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Dotted path for the new document"},"initial_contents":{"type":"string","description":"Optional initial HTML"}},"required":["name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name pair parent leaf doc initial |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			pair:: parentNamespaceAndLeaf: name.
			parent:: pair at: 1.
			leaf:: pair at: 2.
			(parent includesKey: leaf asSymbol) ifTrue: [
				Error signal: 'An entry named ', leaf, ' already exists at this path'
			].
			initial:: (input includesKey: 'initial_contents')
				ifTrue: [input at: 'initial_contents']
				ifFalse: [nil].
			doc:: initial isNil
				ifTrue: [ide documents freshDocumentNamed: leaf asSymbol]
				ifFalse: [ide documents
					freshDocumentNamed: leaf asSymbol
					initialText: initial].
			parent at: leaf asSymbol put: doc.
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Created document ', name
		]
)

setDocumentContentsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'set_document_contents'
		description: 'Replace the HTML contents of an existing Ampleforth document. The previous contents are lost — describe the change to the user before calling. Use get_document first if you need to know the current state.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"},"contents":{"type":"string","description":"New HTML contents"}},"required":["name","contents"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name doc |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			doc:: documentAt: name.
			doc contents: (input at: 'contents').
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Updated contents of ', name
		]
)

deleteDocumentTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'delete_document'
		description: 'Remove an Ampleforth document from its namespace. Destructive; describe the action to the user first.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"}},"required":["name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name pair parent leaf entry |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			pair:: parentNamespaceAndLeaf: name.
			parent:: pair at: 1.
			leaf:: pair at: 2.
			entry:: parent at: leaf asSymbol ifAbsent: [
				Error signal: 'No such entry: ', name
			].
			entry isKindOfDocument ifFalse: [
				Error signal: name, ' is a ', (kindOf: entry),
					', not a document; refusing to delete via this tool.'
			].
			parent removeKey: leaf asSymbol.
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Deleted document ', name
		]
)

listAmpletsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'list_amplets'
		description: 'List the amplets in a document. Each amplet is reported as a fenced block: a header line "=== [INDEX] ampletId=ID ===" followed by the amplet''s Newspeak expression. The ampletId is stable within an editing session but gets renumbered when the document is reloaded from disk — do not assume ids persist across sessions.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"}},"required":["name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name doc container amplets count i result |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			doc:: documentAt: name.
			container:: parseAmpletContainer: doc contents.
			amplets:: container getElementsByClassName: 'ampleforth'.
			count:: amplets at: 'length'.
			count = 0
				ifTrue: ['No amplets in ', name]
				ifFalse: [
					result:: 'Amplets in ', name, ' (', count printString, '):\n'.
					i:: 0.
					[i < count] whileTrue: [
						| amplet aid expr |
						amplet:: amplets at: i.
						aid:: amplet getAttribute: 'ampletId'.
						aid isNil ifTrue: [aid:: '?'].
						expr:: amplet getAttribute: 'name'.
						expr isNil ifTrue: [expr:: ''].
						result:: result, '=== [', i printString, '] ampletId=', aid, ' ===\n',
							expr, '\n'.
						i:: i + 1
					].
					result
				]
		]
)

addAmpletTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'add_amplet'
		description: 'Append a new amplet to a document. The amplet''s expression (the "name" attribute) is the supplied Newspeak expression, evaluated against the host Document when the document renders. A fresh ampletId is allocated automatically. Returns the new ampletId. Destructive — describe the change to the user before calling. v1 always appends at the end; targeted placement will come later.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"},"expression":{"type":"string","description":"Newspeak expression for the amplet (the name attribute)"}},"required":["name","expression"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name expr doc container newId jsDoc newAmplet body bodies |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			expr:: input at: 'expression'.
			doc:: documentAt: name.
			container:: parseAmpletContainer: doc contents.
			(* The document body lives inside a wrapping <div class="self_ampleforth">
			   (the editable "blue box"); append the new amplet there so it lands
			   inside the document boundary, not as a sibling of the wrapper. Fall
			   back to the container if no such wrapper is present. *)
			bodies:: container getElementsByClassName: 'self_ampleforth'.
			body:: (bodies at: 'length') > 0
				ifTrue: [bodies at: 0]
				ifFalse: [container].
			newId:: doc nextAmpletId printString.
			jsDoc:: retainedPlatform js global at: 'document'.
			newAmplet:: jsDoc createElement: 'div'.
			newAmplet setAttribute: 'class' to: 'ampleforth'.
			newAmplet setAttribute: 'ampletId' to: newId.
			newAmplet setAttribute: 'name' to: expr.
			newAmplet setAttribute: 'contenteditable' to: 'false'.
			body appendChild: newAmplet.
			doc contents: (container at: 'innerHTML').
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Added amplet to ', name, ' (ampletId=', newId, ')'
		]
)

setAmpletExpressionTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'set_amplet_expression'
		description: 'Change the Newspeak expression of an existing amplet, identified by ampletId. Destructive — describe the change to the user before calling.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"},"amplet_id":{"type":"string","description":"The ampletId of the amplet to modify (from list_amplets)"},"expression":{"type":"string","description":"New Newspeak expression for the name attribute"}},"required":["name","amplet_id","expression"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name aid expr doc container amplet |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			aid:: input at: 'amplet_id'.
			expr:: input at: 'expression'.
			doc:: documentAt: name.
			container:: parseAmpletContainer: doc contents.
			amplet:: findAmpletWithId: aid in: container.
			amplet setAttribute: 'name' to: expr.
			doc contents: (container at: 'innerHTML').
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Updated amplet ', aid, ' in ', name
		]
)

deleteAmpletTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'delete_amplet'
		description: 'Remove an amplet from a document, identified by ampletId. Destructive — describe the change to the user before calling.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"},"amplet_id":{"type":"string","description":"The ampletId of the amplet to delete (from list_amplets)"}},"required":["name","amplet_id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name aid doc container amplet parent |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			aid:: input at: 'amplet_id'.
			doc:: documentAt: name.
			container:: parseAmpletContainer: doc contents.
			amplet:: findAmpletWithId: aid in: container.
			parent:: amplet at: 'parentNode'.
			parent removeChild: amplet.
			doc contents: (container at: 'innerHTML').
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Deleted amplet ', aid, ' from ', name
		]
)

listMediaTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'list_media'
		description: 'List the media entries (images, audio, video blobs) attached to a document. Returns one line per entry with its path, MIME type, and size in bytes.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"}},"required":["name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name doc reg result |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			doc:: documentAt: name.
			reg:: doc mediaRegistry.
			reg isEmpty
				ifTrue: ['No media in ', name]
				ifFalse: [
					result:: 'Media in ', name, ' (', reg size printString, '):\n'.
					reg keysAndValuesDo: [:path :blob |
						| mime |
						mime:: blob at: 'type'.
						mime isNil ifTrue: [mime:: '?'].
						result:: result, '  ', path,
							'  type=', mime,
							'  size=', (blob at: 'size') printString, '\n'
					].
					result
				]
		]
)

deleteMediaTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'delete_media'
		description: 'Remove a media entry from a document''s media registry, identified by its path. Destructive — describe the change to the user first. If the document''s HTML or any amplet expression references this path, those references will dangle.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"},"path":{"type":"string","description":"The media path (from list_media)"}},"required":["name","path"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| name path doc reg |
			name:: input at: 'name'.
			path:: input at: 'path'.
			doc:: documentAt: name.
			reg:: doc mediaRegistry.
			(reg includesKey: path) ifFalse: [
				Error signal: 'No media entry "', path, '" in ', name
			].
			reg removeKey: path.
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Deleted media ', path, ' from ', name
		]
)

getDocumentTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_document'
		description: 'Get the textual contents of an IDE document (e.g. a literate/Ampleforth document stored in a namespace). Specify the document name or a dotted path to its location in the namespace tree.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path (e.g. \"MyNotes\")."}},"required":["name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| path entry |
			path:: input at: 'name'.
			entry:: resolveNamespacePath: path.
			entry isKindOfDocument ifFalse: [
				Error signal: 'Not a document: ', path, ' (it is a ', (kindOf: entry), ')'
			].
			entry contents
		]
)

searchClassesTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'search_classes'
		description: 'Search for classes whose name contains the given substring. Searches both top-level and nested classes.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"type":"string","description":"Substring to search for in class names (case-sensitive)"}},"required":["query"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| query result count |
			query:: input at: 'query'.
			result:: 'Classes matching "', query, '":\n'.
			count:: 0.
			systemScope allClassesDo: [:cdm |
				(cdm simpleName includesSubstring: query) ifTrue: [
					count:: count + 1.
					result:: result, '  ', (formatAccess: cdm accessModifier),
						(qualifiedNameOf: cdm), '\n'.
				].
			].
			count = 0 ifTrue: [
				result:: result, '  (none found)\n'.
			].
			result
		]
)

navigateToClassTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'navigate_to_class'
		description: 'Navigate the IDE to a class, opening a class presenter on it. Use a dotted path for nested classes (e.g. "ShapeLibrary.Circle"). Side effect: the IDE jumps; use only when the user has expressed intent to navigate.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| cdm |
			cdm:: resolveClassPath: (input at: 'class_name').
			ide browsing navigateTo: (ide browsing ClassSubject onDeclaration: cdm).
			'Opened class ', (qualifiedNameOf: cdm)
		]
)

navigateToNamespaceTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'navigate_to_namespace'
		description: 'Navigate the IDE to a namespace, opening a namespace presenter. With no argument (or empty path), opens Root. Use a dotted path for nested namespaces (e.g. "Icons" or "Root.Icons"). Side effect: the IDE jumps.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"path":{"type":"string","description":"Optional dotted path. Empty or omitted means Root."}}}'
		handler: [:input |
			| path subject |
			path:: (input includesKey: 'path')
				ifTrue: [input at: 'path']
				ifFalse: [''].
			subject:: namespaceSubjectForPath: path.
			ide browsing navigateTo: subject.
			'Opened namespace ', subject title
		]
)

navigateToDocumentTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'navigate_to_document'
		description: 'Navigate the IDE to an Ampleforth document by name or dotted path. Side effect: the IDE jumps.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"type":"string","description":"Document name or dotted path"}},"required":["name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| path entry |
			path:: input at: 'name'.
			entry:: resolveNamespacePath: path.
			entry isKindOfDocument ifFalse: [
				Error signal: 'Not a document: ', path, ' (it is a ', (kindOf: entry), ')'
			].
			ide browsing navigateTo: (ide documents DocumentSubject onModel: entry).
			'Opened document ', path
		]
)

showTestsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'show_tests'
		description: 'Open the test-suite view for a test configuration class — equivalent to clicking the [show tests] link on a test configuration''s class entry. Pass the test configuration class''s dotted path. This does not run the suite.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Test configuration class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| cdm classSubject |
			cdm:: resolveClassPath: (input at: 'class_name').
			classSubject:: ide browsing ClassSubject onDeclaration: cdm.
			classSubject isTestConfiguration ifFalse: [
				Error signal: (qualifiedNameOf: cdm), ' is not a test configuration class'
			].
			ide browsing navigateTo: classSubject inactiveTestingSubject.
			'Opened test suite for ', (qualifiedNameOf: cdm)
		]
)

runTestsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'run_tests'
		description: 'Run the test suite for a test configuration class — equivalent to clicking the [run tests] link on a test configuration''s class entry. The IDE jumps to the in-progress test view; if the test runner raises, the IDE navigates to a debugging thread subject instead. Pass the test configuration class''s dotted path.

The Tester instance is captured for subsequent calls to get_test_results, run_failing_tests, run_erroring_tests, and run_test.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Test configuration class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| cdm classSubject testSubject thread |
			cdm:: resolveClassPath: (input at: 'class_name').
			classSubject:: ide browsing ClassSubject onDeclaration: cdm.
			classSubject isTestConfiguration ifFalse: [
				Error signal: (qualifiedNameOf: cdm), ' is not a test configuration class'
			].
			testSubject:: classSubject testingSubject.
			testersByConfigName at: cdm simpleName asString put: testSubject.
			thread:: ActivationMirror invokeSuspended:
				[ide browsing navigateTo: testSubject].
			thread resume.
			thread isFulfilled ifFalse: [
				ide browsing navigateTo: (ide debugging ThreadSubject onModel: thread)
			].
			'Running tests for ', (qualifiedNameOf: cdm),
				'. Use get_test_results to retrieve outcomes when complete.'
		]
)

(* --- Test result helpers --- *)

testerForConfigPath: configClassPath <String> ^ <Object> = (
	| cdm testSubject |
	cdm:: resolveClassPath: configClassPath.
	testSubject:: testersByConfigName at: cdm simpleName asString ifAbsent: [
		Error signal: 'No test run cached for ', configClassPath,
			'. Call run_tests first.'
	].
	^testSubject tester
)

testCaseId: testCase <Object> ^ <String> = (
	^testCase environment name asString, ' >> ', testCase selector asString
)

findTestCase: testName <String> inTester: tester <Object> ^ <Object> = (
	| all match |
	all:: List new.
	tester errors    do: [:r  | all add: r testCase].
	tester failures  do: [:r  | all add: r testCase].
	tester successes do: [:r  | all add: r testCase].
	tester inactive  do: [:tc | all add: tc].
	match:: all detect: [:tc | (testCaseId: tc) = testName] ifNone: [nil].
	match isNil ifTrue: [
		Error signal: 'No test named "', testName, '" in this config''s suite.'
	].
	^match
)

summarizeFailure: r <Object> ^ <String> = (
	^[r description] on: Error do: [:e | '(no description)']
)

summarizeError: r <Object> ^ <String> = (
	^[
		r exception class name asString, ': ', r exception messageText
	] on: Error do: [:e | '(unprintable exception)']
)

formatTestSummary: tester <Object> configPath: configPath <String> ^ <String> = (
	| sb total complete ratio |
	total:: [tester testCaseList size] on: Error do: [:e | 0].
	complete:: tester errors size + tester failures size + tester successes size.
	ratio:: total = 0 ifTrue: [1.0] ifFalse: [complete asFloat / total].
	sb:: 'Test config: ', configPath, '\n'.
	sb:: sb, 'Status: ', complete printString, ' of ', total printString,
		' tests complete (', ((ratio * 100) rounded) printString, '%)\n'.
	sb:: sb, '  Passed:   ', tester successes size printString, '\n'.
	sb:: sb, '  Failed:   ', tester failures  size printString, '\n'.
	sb:: sb, '  Errored:  ', tester errors    size printString, '\n'.
	sb:: sb, '  Disabled: ', tester disabled  size printString, '\n'.
	sb:: sb, '  Inactive: ', tester inactive  size printString,
		' (not yet run or not part of last selection)\n'.
	tester failures isEmpty ifFalse: [
		sb:: sb, '\nFailures:\n'.
		tester failures do: [:r |
			sb:: sb, '  [', (testCaseId: r testCase), '] ', (summarizeFailure: r), '\n'
		]
	].
	tester errors isEmpty ifFalse: [
		sb:: sb, '\nErrors:\n'.
		tester errors do: [:r |
			sb:: sb, '  [', (testCaseId: r testCase), '] ', (summarizeError: r), '\n'
		]
	].
	complete < total ifTrue: [
		sb:: sb, '\n(Tests may still be running; call get_test_results again later for an updated snapshot.)\n'
	].
	^sb
)

getTestResultsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_test_results'
		description: 'Retrieve outcomes from the most recent run_tests (or selective re-run) for a test configuration class. Returns counts of passed / failed / errored / disabled / inactive plus one-line summaries of each failure and error. Use get_test_failure_details for full info on a specific test.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Test configuration class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| configPath tester |
			configPath:: input at: 'class_name'.
			tester:: testerForConfigPath: configPath.
			formatTestSummary: tester configPath: configPath
		]
)

getTestFailureDetailsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_test_failure_details'
		description: 'Get full detail on a single failure or error from the most recent test run. test_name is the id formatted as "ContextName >> test_selector" — exactly as it appears in get_test_results.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Test configuration class name or dotted path"},"test_name":{"type":"string","description":"ContextName >> test_selector form"}},"required":["class_name","test_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| configPath testName tester testCase failureResult errorResult successResult result |
			configPath:: input at: 'class_name'.
			testName:: input at: 'test_name'.
			tester:: testerForConfigPath: configPath.
			testCase:: findTestCase: testName inTester: tester.
			failureResult:: tester failures detect: [:r | r testCase = testCase] ifNone: [nil].
			errorResult:: tester errors detect: [:r | r testCase = testCase] ifNone: [nil].
			successResult:: tester successes detect: [:r | r testCase = testCase] ifNone: [nil].
			failureResult isNil ifFalse: [
				^'[', testName, '] FAILURE\nDescription: ', (summarizeFailure: failureResult)
			].
			errorResult isNil ifFalse: [
				^'[', testName, '] ERROR\n',
					'Exception class: ', ([errorResult exception class name asString]
						on: Error do: [:e | '(unknown)']), '\n',
					'Message: ', ([errorResult exception messageText]
						on: Error do: [:e | '(unprintable)']), '\n',
					'(For full stack, navigate to the testing view and click the test in the IDE.)'
			].
			successResult isNil ifFalse: [
				^'[', testName, '] PASSED — no failure detail to report.'
			].
			'[', testName, '] is inactive — not run in the latest invocation.'
		]
)

runTestsForCases: testCases <Object> tester: tester <Object> = (
	(* Run each test case in turn through tester run:, which mutates the
	   tester''s errors / failures / successes lists. Iterate over a copy
	   because run: removes-then-adds. *)
	(testCases copyFrom: 1 to: testCases size) do: [:tc |
		[tester run: tc] on: Error do: [:e | ]
	]
)

runFailingTestsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'run_failing_tests'
		description: 'Re-run only the failing tests from the most recent run. Updates the cached Tester in place. The IDE testing view (if currently displayed) refreshes to show the new state.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Test configuration class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| configPath tester count |
			configPath:: input at: 'class_name'.
			tester:: testerForConfigPath: configPath.
			count:: tester failures size.
			runTestsForCases: (tester failures collect: [:r | r testCase]) tester: tester.
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Re-ran ', count printString, ' failing test',
				(count = 1 ifTrue: [''] ifFalse: ['s']),
				'. Call get_test_results for the new outcome.'
		]
)

runErroringTestsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'run_erroring_tests'
		description: 'Re-run only the erroring tests from the most recent run. Updates the cached Tester in place. The IDE testing view (if currently displayed) refreshes to show the new state.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Test configuration class name or dotted path"}},"required":["class_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| configPath tester count |
			configPath:: input at: 'class_name'.
			tester:: testerForConfigPath: configPath.
			count:: tester errors size.
			runTestsForCases: (tester errors collect: [:r | r testCase]) tester: tester.
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Re-ran ', count printString, ' erroring test',
				(count = 1 ifTrue: [''] ifFalse: ['s']),
				'. Call get_test_results for the new outcome.'
		]
)

runOneTestTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'run_test'
		description: 'Re-run a single test by name. test_name is the "ContextName >> test_selector" form as it appears in get_test_results. The cached Tester is updated in place and the IDE testing view refreshes.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"class_name":{"type":"string","description":"Test configuration class name or dotted path"},"test_name":{"type":"string","description":"ContextName >> test_selector form"}},"required":["class_name","test_name"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| configPath testName tester testCase |
			configPath:: input at: 'class_name'.
			testName:: input at: 'test_name'.
			tester:: testerForConfigPath: configPath.
			testCase:: findTestCase: testName inTester: tester.
			[tester run: testCase] on: Error do: [:e |
				Error signal: 'Re-run failed: ', e messageText
			].
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Re-ran [', testName, ']. Call get_test_results for the new outcome.'
		]
)

proposeChangesTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'propose_changes'
		description: 'Stage a set of code edits for atomic installation. Does NOT install. Returns a textual diff plus a changeset id. After calling this, present the diff to the user and wait for explicit approval ("apply", "ok", "go ahead") before calling apply_changeset. If the user wants something different, refine the changes and propose again.

Each entry in the changes array is one of:
- {kind: "add_or_replace_method",       class_name, side?, source}
- {kind: "delete_method",               class_name, side?, selector}
- {kind: "add_or_replace_lazy_slot",    class_name, side?, source}
- {kind: "delete_lazy_slot",            class_name, side?, selector}
- {kind: "set_class_header",            class_name, source}
- {kind: "add_or_replace_nested_class", class_name, source}  -- class_name is the ENCLOSING class
- {kind: "delete_nested_class",         class_name}          -- class_name is the nested class to remove
- {kind: "add_top_level_class",         class_name, source}  -- class_name must match the simpleName in source

class_name is a dotted path; side defaults to "instance" for member ops. source is full Newspeak source. Multiple changes in one call install atomically — use this for mutually dependent edits.

Top-level class DELETION is not supported by this tool (different mechanism, not part of atomic install). Renaming a class is not supported either; set_class_header preserves the simple name.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"changes":{"type":"array","items":{"type":"object","properties":{"kind":{"type":"string","enum":["add_or_replace_method","delete_method","add_or_replace_lazy_slot","delete_lazy_slot","set_class_header","add_or_replace_nested_class","delete_nested_class","add_top_level_class"]},"class_name":{"type":"string"},"side":{"type":"string","enum":["instance","class"]},"selector":{"type":"string"},"source":{"type":"string"}},"required":["kind","class_name"]}}},"required":["changes"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| changes records id |
			changes:: input at: 'changes'.
			records:: List new.
			(* changes is a JS array, not a Newspeak Collection; iterate by index. *)
			0 to: (changes at: 'length') - 1 do: [:i |
				records add: (validateChange: (changes at: i))
			].
			records isEmpty ifTrue: [
				Error signal: 'No changes provided'
			].
			id:: freshChangesetId.
			proposedChangesets at: id put: records.
			formatChangesetId: id records: records
		]
)

applyChangesetTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'apply_changeset'
		description: 'Atomically install a previously proposed changeset. Call this only after the user has reviewed the diff returned by propose_changes and explicitly approved. On success returns "Applied changeset <id>". On failure the atomic install rolls back, so no partial state is left in the running system.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"id":{"type":"string","description":"The changeset id returned by propose_changes"}},"required":["id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id records |
			id:: input at: 'id'.
			records:: proposedChangesets at: id ifAbsent: [
				Error signal: 'No such changeset: ', id, ' (already applied, discarded, or never proposed)'
			].
			applyChangesetRecords: records.
			proposedChangesets removeKey: id.
			'Applied changeset ', id
		]
)

evaluateTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'evaluate'
		description: 'Evaluate a Newspeak expression. By default the receiver is the AI workspace (id "workspace") — a regular IDE workspace named AIWorkspace, with platform, ide, and Root accessible via the Workspace superclass. Pass in_id to evaluate with a previously registered object as the receiver.

Non-primitive results are registered in the object registry under an auto-generated id (e.g. "r3") or your chosen name (via the name parameter). Primitives (Integer, Float, String, Symbol, Boolean, Character, nil) are NOT registered — their printString is just returned.

Side-effecting expressions (collection mutations, slot assignments via setters, etc.) are allowed — this is the REPL primitive. Use propose_changes / apply_changeset for code installation, not raw evaluate.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"expression":{"type":"string","description":"Newspeak expression to evaluate"},"in_id":{"type":"string","description":"Id of registered receiver (default: workspace)"},"name":{"type":"string","description":"Optional friendly id for the result, instead of auto-generated rN"}},"required":["expression"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| exprSource inId nameOrNil receiver thread resultMirror |
			exprSource:: input at: 'expression'.
			inId:: (input includesKey: 'in_id')
				ifTrue: [input at: 'in_id']
				ifFalse: [
					(* Default to whatever evaluator the user has focused on
					   (workspace, object inspector, method evaluator,
					   debugger activation). Falls through to the AI
					   workspace when no evaluator focus is set. *)
					focusKind = #evaluator
						ifTrue: ['focus']
						ifFalse: ['workspace']
				].
			nameOrNil:: (input includesKey: 'name')
				ifTrue: [input at: 'name']
				ifFalse: [nil].
			receiver:: mirrorForObjectId: inId.
			thread:: [receiver evaluate: exprSource] on: Error do: [:e |
				Error signal: 'Evaluation failed at compile: ', e messageText
			].
			(* When evaluating against an in-IDE evaluator (the workspace via
			   id 'workspace', or whatever the user has focused on via
			   id 'focus'), append the ThreadMirror to that evaluator's
			   results list so the result becomes visible in the IDE — both
			   live (we trigger updateCurrentDisplay) and on later
			   navigation. For arbitrary objects from the registry, there
			   is no associated presenter to update; the AI sees the result
			   via its returned id and tools, which is enough for v1.
			   All best-effort — never let an exposure failure mask the
			   actual evaluation result. *)
			inId = 'workspace' ifTrue: [
				[aiWorkspaceSubject evaluator results add: thread]
					on: Error do: [:e | ].
				ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay
			] ifFalse: [
				inId = 'focus' ifTrue: [
					focusEvaluatorSubject_slot isNil ifFalse: [
						[focusEvaluatorSubject_slot results add: thread]
							on: Error do: [:e | ]
					].
					ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay
				]
			].
			thread isBroken ifTrue: [
				| ex topFrame frameId frameNote |
				ex:: [thread result reflectee printString]
					on: Error do: [:e | '(broken; unprintable)'].
				(* Register the top stack frame so the AI can immediately
				   inspect the failure. *)
				topFrame:: [thread suspendedActivation] on: Error do: [:e | nil].
				frameId:: topFrame isNil
					ifTrue: [nil]
					ifFalse: [registerActivation: topFrame].
				frameNote:: frameId isNil
					ifTrue: ['']
					ifFalse: [' Top frame registered as ', frameId,
						'; use get_stack_trace to inspect.'].
				Error signal: 'Evaluation raised at runtime: ', ex, '.', frameNote
			].
			resultMirror:: thread result.
			(* Use ifTrue:ifFalse: rather than ^early-return: this is a stored
			   handler block whose enclosing method (evaluateTool) has already
			   returned, so ^ would raise CannotReturn. *)
			(isPrimitiveResult: resultMirror)
				ifTrue: ['=> ', (summaryOf: resultMirror)]
				ifFalse: [
					| id |
					id:: registerResult: resultMirror withName: nameOrNil.
					'=> [', id, '] ', (summaryOf: resultMirror)
				]
		]
)

navigateToObjectTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'navigate_to_object'
		description: 'Navigate the IDE to an object presenter on a registered object. Pass the id from evaluate or list_objects. Side effect: the IDE jumps.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"id":{"type":"string","description":"Registered object id (e.g. r1, or workspace)"}},"required":["id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id mirror |
			id:: input at: 'id'.
			mirror:: mirrorForObjectId: id.
			ide browsing navigateTo: (ide browsing ObjectSubject onModel: mirror).
			'Opened object [', id, '] ', (summaryOf: mirror)
		]
)

inspectObjectTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'inspect_object'
		description: 'Get a short summary of a registered object — class name and printString. To enumerate the messages it responds to, follow up with list_class_members on the class.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id mirror |
			id:: input at: 'id'.
			mirror:: mirrorForObjectId: id.
			'Object [', id, ']\nClass: ', (mirror getClass mixin name asString),
				'\nprintString: ', ([mirror reflectee printString]
					on: Error do: [:e | '(raised: ', e messageText, ')'])
		]
)

listObjectsTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'list_objects'
		description: 'List all objects registered in the AI object registry, with their ids and summaries. Includes the always-present workspace.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{}}'
		handler: [:input |
			(* Ensure workspace is registered. *)
			| result |
			aiWorkspaceMirror.
			result:: 'Registered objects:\n'.
			objectRegistry keysAndValuesDo: [:id :m |
				result:: result, '  [', id, '] ', (summaryOf: m), '\n'
			].
			result
		]
)

(* --- Debugger helpers (Phase 1: observation) --- *)

formatMethodNameOf: anActivationMirror ^ <String> = (
	(* Best-effort "Class >> selector" for a frame. *)
	^[
		| m mixinDecl |
		m:: anActivationMirror method.
		mixinDecl:: m definingMixin declaration.
		(qualifiedNameOf: mixinDecl), ' >> ', m name asString
	] on: Exception do: [:e | '(unknown method)']
)

formatActivationLine: anActivationMirror id: id ^ <String> = (
	^'[', id, '] ', (formatMethodNameOf: anActivationMirror)
)

formatSourceWithRange: source <String> range: rangeOrNil <Object> ^ <String> = (
	(* Append a structured marker for the active range rather than splicing
	   into the source text — easier for the AI to read at a glance. *)
	| header |
	header:: rangeOrNil isNil
		ifTrue: ['active: (no range info)']
		ifFalse: ['active: source positions ', rangeOrNil start printString,
			'..', rangeOrNil stop printString].
	^header, String lf, '---', String lf, source
)

getCurrentFrameTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_current_frame'
		description: 'Return the registered activation id of the currently-focused debugger frame / method evaluator / lazy-slot evaluator. Raises if no activation focus is set. Use this to bootstrap into get_stack_trace, inspect_activation, etc. from a user-driven debug session.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{}}'
		handler: [:input |
			(focusKind = #evaluator
				and: [focusEvaluatorMirror_slot isNil not
					and: [focusEvaluatorMirror_slot isKindOfActivationMirror]])
				ifTrue: [
					| id |
					id:: registerActivation: focusEvaluatorMirror_slot.
					'Current frame: ', (formatActivationLine: focusEvaluatorMirror_slot id: id)
				]
				ifFalse: [
					Error signal: 'No activation is currently focused. Click a brain on a debugger frame, method evaluator, or lazy-slot evaluator first.'
				]
		]
)

getStackTraceTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_stack_trace'
		description: 'Walk the call stack starting at the given activation, going down through callers via sender. Each frame is (re)registered under its aN id so you can evaluate(in_id: "aN"), inspect_activation(id: "aN"), etc. Pass either the activation id from get_current_frame or the id returned in a broken-evaluate error message.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"activation_id":{"type":"string","description":"Registered activation id (e.g. a1)"}},"required":["activation_id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| startId start result frame depth |
			startId:: input at: 'activation_id'.
			start:: activationForId: startId.
			result:: 'Stack from [', startId, '] downward:', String lf.
			frame:: start.
			depth:: 0.
			[frame isNil] whileFalse: [
				| id |
				id:: registerActivation: frame.
				result:: result, '  ', depth printString, '. ',
					(formatActivationLine: frame id: id), String lf.
				frame:: [frame sender] on: Error do: [:e | nil].
				depth:: depth + 1
			].
			result
		]
)

getCurrentExpressionTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'get_current_expression'
		description: 'Return the method source for an activation, with a structured marker giving the source positions of the currently-executing (or paused) expression. Format is: a header line ("active: source positions N..M"), a separator, then the method source verbatim. The N..M positions index into the source string (1-based inclusive of start, exclusive of stop).'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"activation_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["activation_id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id activation source range |
			id:: input at: 'activation_id'.
			activation:: activationForId: id.
			source:: [activation method source] on: Exception do: [:e | '(source unavailable)'].
			range:: [activation sourceRange] on: Exception do: [:e | nil].
			'Frame [', id, '] ', (formatMethodNameOf: activation), String lf,
				(formatSourceWithRange: source range: range)
		]
)

(* --- Debugger helpers (Phase 2: control) --- *)

threadStateName: thread ^ <String> = (
	[thread isFulfilled  ifTrue: [^'fulfilled']]  on: Exception do: [:e | ].
	[thread isBroken     ifTrue: [^'broken']]     on: Exception do: [:e | ].
	[thread isSuspended  ifTrue: [^'suspended']]  on: Exception do: [:e | ].
	[thread isTerminated ifTrue: [^'terminated']] on: Exception do: [:e | ].
	^'unknown'
)

pruneDeadActivations = (
	(* Remove from the registry any aN that points at an activation that
	   is no longer continuable (frame has unwound or thread fulfilled). *)
	| dead |
	dead:: List new.
	objectRegistry keysAndValuesDo: [:k :v |
		(((k size > 0 and: [(k at: 1) = 'a' first])
			and: [v isKindOfActivationMirror])
			and: [[v isUncontinuable] on: Exception do: [:e | true]])
			ifTrue: [dead add: k]
	].
	dead do: [:k | objectRegistry removeKey: k]
)

postOperationReport: thread ^ <String> = (
	(* Called after any step/return: report the new thread state, register
	   the result if fulfilled, register the new top frame if still suspended,
	   prune dead activation ids, and clear focus if it pointed at a frame
	   that's gone. Returns a human-readable status fragment. *)
	| status |
	status:: 'thread state: ', (threadStateName: thread).
	([thread isFulfilled] on: Exception do: [:e | false]) ifTrue: [
		| result resultId |
		result:: [thread result] on: Exception do: [:e | nil].
		result isNil ifFalse: [
			resultId:: registerResult: result withName: nil.
			status:: status, '; result registered as ', resultId
		]
	].
	([thread isSuspended] on: Exception do: [:e | false]) ifTrue: [
		| topFrame topId |
		topFrame:: [thread suspendedActivation] on: Exception do: [:e | nil].
		topFrame isNil ifFalse: [
			topId:: registerActivation: topFrame.
			status:: status, '; top frame now [', topId, '] ',
				(formatMethodNameOf: topFrame)
		]
	].
	pruneDeadActivations.
	(focusKind = #evaluator
		and: [focusEvaluatorMirror_slot isNil not
			and: [focusEvaluatorMirror_slot isKindOfActivationMirror
				and: [[focusEvaluatorMirror_slot isUncontinuable]
					on: Exception do: [:e | true]]]])
		ifTrue: [clearFocus].
	^status
)

stepTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'step'
		description: 'Step the thread at a given activation frame. kind is one of: into (step into the next call), over (step over it), out (run until this frame returns), through (step into closure), restart (re-execute this frame from its first statement). After the step, the report names the new top frame if the thread is still suspended; registers the result and reports it if the thread fulfills; cleans up activations that are no longer reachable. The IDE debugger view is refreshed.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"activation_id":{"type":"string"},"kind":{"type":"string","enum":["into","over","out","through","restart"]}},"required":["activation_id","kind"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id kind activation newThread |
			id:: input at: 'activation_id'.
			kind:: input at: 'kind'.
			activation:: activationForId: id.
			newThread:: nil.
			kind = 'into'    ifTrue: [newThread:: activation stepInto].
			kind = 'over'    ifTrue: [newThread:: activation stepOver].
			kind = 'out'     ifTrue: [newThread:: activation stepOut].
			kind = 'through' ifTrue: [newThread:: activation stepThrough].
			kind = 'restart' ifTrue: [newThread:: activation restart].
			newThread isNil ifTrue: [
				Error signal: 'Unknown step kind: ', kind
			].
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Stepped (', kind, ') from [', id, ']; ',
				(postOperationReport: newThread)
		]
)

continueThreadTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'continue_thread'
		description: 'Resume the thread that the given activation belongs to — equivalent to the debugger''s Continue button. The thread runs until it fulfills, breaks again, or is otherwise suspended. State after is reported the same way as for step / return_from.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"activation_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["activation_id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id activation threadMirror |
			id:: input at: 'activation_id'.
			activation:: activationForId: id.
			threadMirror:: activation threadMirror.
			threadMirror resume.
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			'Resumed thread of [', id, ']; ',
				(postOperationReport: threadMirror)
		]
)

returnFromTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'return_from'
		description: 'Force the given activation to return immediately, using the result of evaluating expression in that frame''s scope as the method''s return value. Locals (self, args, temps) are in scope inside expression. The thread resumes; subsequent state is reported the same way as for step. Use with care — this short-circuits whatever the method would otherwise compute.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"activation_id":{"type":"string"},"expression":{"type":"string"}},"required":["activation_id","expression"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id expr activation evalThread resultMirror newThread valueStr |
			id:: input at: 'activation_id'.
			expr:: input at: 'expression'.
			activation:: activationForId: id.
			evalThread:: [activation evaluate: expr] on: Exception do: [:e |
				Error signal: 'Failed to compile return expression: ', e messageText
			].
			evalThread isBroken ifTrue: [
				| ex |
				ex:: [evalThread result reflectee printString]
					on: Exception do: [:e | '(unprintable)'].
				Error signal: 'Return expression raised: ', ex
			].
			resultMirror:: evalThread result.
			newThread:: activation return: resultMirror.
			ide browsing updateCurrentDisplay.
			valueStr:: [resultMirror reflectee printString]
				on: Exception do: [:e | '(unprintable)'].
			'Returned from [', id, '] with value ', valueStr, '; ',
				(postOperationReport: newThread)
		]
)

inspectActivationTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'inspect_activation'
		description: 'Summarise an activation frame: defining class, method selector, and a listing of locals (self, args, temps) with their printString. To dig further, call evaluate(in_id: "aN", expression: ...) — locals are in scope by name, self is the activation''s receiver.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"activation_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["activation_id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id activation result continuableNote slotsNote |
			id:: input at: 'activation_id'.
			activation:: activationForId: id.
			(* Each section is bracketed independently with on: Exception (not
			   just Error) so a single misbehaving frame can't fail the whole
			   tool — failures in one section degrade to a placeholder. *)
			result:: 'Frame [', id, '] ',
				([formatMethodNameOf: activation]
					on: Exception do: [:e | '(method name unavailable)']),
				String lf.
			continuableNote:: [
				activation isUncontinuable
					ifTrue: ['no (frame is dead)']
					ifFalse: ['yes']
			] on: Exception do: [:e | '(unknown)'].
			result:: result, 'Continuable: ', continuableNote, String lf.
			slotsNote:: [
				| slots sb |
				slots:: activation slots.
				slots isEmpty ifTrue: [
					'  (no locals)'
				] ifFalse: [
					sb:: ''.
					slots do: [:s |
						| nameStr valueStr |
						nameStr:: [s name asString]
							on: Exception do: [:e | '(?)'].
						valueStr:: [s value reflectee printString]
							on: Exception do: [:e | '(unprintable)'].
						valueStr size > 120 ifTrue: [
							valueStr:: (valueStr copyFrom: 1 to: 117), '...'
						].
						sb:: sb, '  ', nameStr, ' = ', valueStr, String lf
					].
					sb
				]
			] on: Exception do: [:e |
				'  (slot enumeration raised: ', e messageText, ')'
			].
			result:: result, 'Locals:', String lf, slotsNote.
			result
		]
)

forgetObjectTool ^ <Tool> = (
	^Tool
		name: 'forget_object'
		description: 'Remove an object from the registry. The workspace itself cannot be forgotten.'
		inputSchema: '{"type":"object","properties":{"id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["id"]}'
		handler: [:input |
			| id |
			id:: input at: 'id'.
			id = 'workspace' ifTrue: [
				Error signal: 'Cannot forget the workspace.'
			].
			objectRegistry at: id ifAbsent: [
				Error signal: 'No such object id: ', id
			].
			objectRegistry removeKey: id.
			'Forgot [', id, ']'
		]
)

(* --- Convenience API --- *)

(* Create a session with the IDE tools pre-configured. *)
public createSessionWithProvider: provider <Provider> ^ <Session> = (
	| session |
	session:: Session provider: provider tools: tools.
	session systemPrompt: newspeakSystemPrompt.
	^session
)

(* Create a ChatSubject backed by a new session with IDE tools. *)
public createChatWithProvider: provider <Provider> ^ <IDEChatSubject> = (
	^IDEChatSubject onModel: (createSessionWithProvider: provider)
)

(* System prompt — Newspeak cheat sheet, cached by AnthropicProvider. *)
public newspeakSystemPrompt ^ <String> = (
	^'You are a programming assistant for the Newspeak programming language, embedded in the Newspeak Web IDE. Use the tools listed below to look up actual definitions in the user''s running IDE rather than guessing from training — Newspeak documentation is sparse and recall is unreliable. Prefer concise answers; when the user asks about code, show the source you found via tools.

# Newspeak essentials

Newspeak is a pure message-based, object-capability language in the Smalltalk family.

- No global namespace, no static state, no class variables, no pool variables.
- Names are always method invocations (auto-generated getters); there are no variable references.
- No assignment operator; slot writes happen through generated setters.
- Method invocation is the only operation: e m is always a send. There is no dot between receiver and selector.
- Classes nest arbitrarily. Inheritance is via mixins; the superclass clause is itself a message send.

# Class declarations

A class header has the form:
  class Name primaryFactoryHeader = SuperFactory (| slots |) ( instanceMembers ) : ( classSideMembers )

The first parenthesized block after = is the instance initializer (slot declarations plus setup code). The next parenthesized block is the body of instance-side members. The optional ": (...)" declares class-side members.

Examples:

  class Point x: i y: j = (| public x ::= i. public y ::= j. |) (
    public printString = (^''x='', x printString, '' y='', y printString)
  ) : ()

  class ShapeLibrary usingPlatform: platform = (
    | private List = platform collections List. |) (
    public class Shape = ( ... )( ... ) : ()
    public class Circle = Shape (...)(...) : ()
  ) : ()

A top-level module definition is a class whose factory takes a manifest or platform parameter. The manifest/platform supplies the module''s dependencies — modules and library objects it needs.

# Slots vs methods (very easy to confuse — these are distinct syntactic forms)

SLOTS sit inside vertical bars |...| and use a bare expression (NO parentheses around the initializer, NO method body).

  | public x = 0.                   "immutable slot, initialized to 0"
    public x ::= 0.                 "mutable slot (auto-generated setter x:)"
    public x.                       "mutable slot, defaults to nil"
    lazy public x = computeIt.      "lazy immutable slot; computeIt is evaluated on first access"
    lazy public x ::= computeIt.    "lazy mutable slot"
    protected y. private z.         "narrower visibility — same forms"
  |

Mutually recursive (simultaneous) slot declarations use double bars: || a = ... . b = ... . ||

METHODS sit OUTSIDE the slot bars and DO use parentheses around the body:

  public m = ( ^expr )
  public m: arg = ( body. ^result )
  public m ^ <ReturnType> = ( body )

The presence or absence of "( ... )" after "=" is the only thing distinguishing a no-arg method from a slot. "lazy slotName = computeIt." is a slot. "lazy slotName = ( computeIt )" is wrong — there is no "lazy" method modifier.

# Setter syntax

- Implicit-receiver setter:  slot:: value.   (short for self slot: value.)
- Explicit-receiver setter:  obj slot: value.
- "::" is ONLY for implicit-receiver setter sends. Never use it with an explicit receiver.

# Sends

Five send forms with distinct visibility rules:

- Ordinary             e m       Receiver e; only public members.
- Self                 self m    Public, protected, private of self''s class.
- Super                super m   Public, protected of superclasses.
- Implicit (here)      m         Looks up in enclosing lexical scope (any modifier), then in self''s superclasses (public/protected).
- Outer                outer C m C names a lexically enclosing class. Reaches members declared in C (any modifier) and public/protected of C''s superclasses.

# Access modifiers

public, protected, private. The default modifier on a declared member is protected.

# Member ordering

Inside a class body, ALL nested-class declarations must precede method declarations. The compiler enforces this.

# Comments and literals

- Comments:  (* ... *)   nestable.
- Strings:   single-quote delimited; doubled apostrophe for a literal quote.
- Symbols:   #foo  #at:put:
- Numbers:   42  3.14
- Booleans:  true  false
- Nil:       nil
- Tuples:    { a. b. c }
- Blocks:    [:x | body]   invoked via value, value:, value:value:, etc.

# Types (advisory only)

Type annotations are unenforced documentation read by the typechecker (a linter). Placement:

- After slot:              public x <Integer> = 0.
- After parameter:         m: x <Integer>
- After method header:     m ^ <Boolean> = ( ... )
- Class generics:          class Map <[K, V]> new: cap = ... ( ... ) : ()
- Generic instantiation:   List[Point]  Map[String, Integer]

# Reflection (mirrors)

Get mirrors from "platform mirrors":

- ClassMirror reflecting: aClass       class mirror.
- ObjectMirror reflecting: anObject    object mirror.

On a ClassMirror:
- mixin                  the MixinMirror.
- mixin declaration      ClassDeclarationMirror (source, header, instanceSide, classSide).
- mixin methods, mixin slots, mixin lazySlots, mixin nestedClasses.

# Platform and IDE namespace

The platform object p exposes capabilities:
  p kernel  p collections  p mirrors  p actors  p js  p hopscotch  p graphics  p fonts  p text

p js global is the JavaScript global namespace.

The IDE maintains an extra-linguistic namespace at "ide namespacing Root" — a Map keyed by Symbol. Sub-namespaces include Icons (image aliens) and Categories. Top-level classes, documents, and other values live directly in Root.

Namespace protocol: at:, at:put:, at:ifAbsent:, keys, keysAndValuesDo:, includesKey:, predicate isKindOfNamespace.

# Ampleforth documents

An Ampleforth document is a live HTML document that mixes prose with embedded live Hopscotch widgets. Documents are first-class IDE entities, stored in the namespace as instances of Document subclasses (one class per named document, nested in the IDE''s documentHolder).

Document slots:
- name <String>
- contents <String>                      the HTML text.
- mediaRegistry <Map[String, Blob]>      embedded media (images, audio, video).

Document inherits from ProgrammingPresenter, so all Hopscotch fragment builders are available (label:, link:, button:, column:, row:, holder:, image:, textDisplay:, ...). This is so amplet expressions evaluated against a Document can use those builders directly.

The get_document tool returns the document''s contents (HTML).

# Amplets

An amplet is a placeholder inside a document''s HTML:

  <div class="ampleforth" ampletId="..." name="EXPR" contenteditable="false"> ... </div>

The "name" attribute is a Newspeak expression. When the document renders, each amplet''s expression is evaluated as a message send against the host Document instance; the resulting Fragment replaces the placeholder.

Because Document inherits from ProgrammingPresenter, amplet expressions can call fragment builders directly, e.g.:

- label: ''Hello''
- button: ''Run'' action: [doSomething]
- inspect: anObject
- evaluate: ''someExpression''
- column: { ... }   row: { ... }

Document also offers addMethodFromSource:, addClassFromSource:, addLazySlotFromSource:, so an amplet can extend its host document''s API mid-document. Document''s doesNotUnderstand: looks up unknown names in Root, so amplets can reach top-level entities directly.

Amplet evaluation is incremental: if an amplet''s expression text hasn''t changed since the last render (tracked by ampletId), the existing fragment is reused — important for preserving UI state.

# Style guidelines

- Whitespace between keyword and argument: "at: 1 put: x" (not "at:1 put:x").
- For a keyword argument that is itself a keyword send, prefer "foo:: x bar: y" over "foo: (x bar: y)".
- Comments precede the construct they describe.
- Never use "::" with an explicit receiver — that is invalid syntax.
- Keep classes before methods inside the class body.

# Navigating nested classes

Classes nest, often several levels deep, and only top-level (module) classes have a unique simple name. Tool output always reports a class by its *dotted path* from the top-level module — e.g. "RuntimeForHopscotchForHTML.Platform.Images" means the class "Images" nested in "Platform" nested in the top-level class "RuntimeForHopscotchForHTML". Treat the leftmost segment as the module that "owns" the definition. Pass the same dotted path back into get_class_source, get_class_header, list_class_members, get_member_source to read or drill into that class.

If you find an inner class by simple name and want to know where it is defined, you can either rely on the dotted path the tools return, or run implementors_of on the class''s own name — the matches will be the enclosing classes'' headers and slots that expose it.

# Using the IDE tools

Prefer tool calls to recalling from training data — many features here are specific to this codebase.

- list_namespace      List entries of a namespace; defaults to Root; dotted paths like Icons or Root.Icons drill in.
- search_classes      Substring search across all classes (including nested), returns dotted paths.
- get_class_source    Full source of a class. Use dotted paths for nested classes (e.g. Outer.Inner).
- get_class_header    Just the header (factory, superclass, slots).
- list_class_members  Structured listing with access modifiers, both sides.
- get_member_source   Source of a method or a lazy slot. Set side: "class" for class-side; default is instance.
- senders_of, implementors_of    Cross-cutting selector lookups across the system.
- get_document        HTML contents of a Document, by name or dotted path.
- create_document     Create a new Document at the given dotted path (parent must be a namespace), optionally with initial HTML.
- set_document_contents  Replace an existing Document''s HTML contents. Destructive — describe the change to the user before calling.
- delete_document     Remove a Document from its namespace. Destructive.
- list_amplets        List the amplets in a document. Each entry: index, ampletId, and the Newspeak expression. Use this before targeting an amplet by id. ampletIds are session-stable but get renumbered on reload, so don''t cache them across sessions.
- add_amplet          Append a new amplet to a document with a given expression. Allocates a fresh ampletId. Destructive (changes the document HTML) — describe the change first. v1 only appends at the end; finer placement will come later.
- set_amplet_expression  Change an existing amplet''s Newspeak expression by ampletId. Destructive — describe first.
- delete_amplet       Remove an amplet by ampletId. Destructive — describe first.
- list_media          List media entries (images, audio, video) attached to a document: path, MIME type, size.
- delete_media        Remove a media entry from a document''s mediaRegistry by path. Destructive — if the document HTML or an amplet references the path, those references will dangle. Check refs first.
- current_focus       What the user is currently asking about — set when the user opens the chat from a presenter or otherwise signals focus. Call this FIRST when the user says "this", "here", "the current method", refers to a member without naming its class, or otherwise speaks deictically. If the focus is "(no focus set)", ask the user or use other tools.
- web_fetch           Fetch any URL and return its text body. Use this when you need the authoritative definition of a Newspeak construct. The published reference material is:
                        - Newspeak Language Specification (grammar in EBNF + prose):
                          https://newspeaklanguage.org/spec/newspeak-spec.tex
                        - Newspeak 2025 Tutorial (PDF; text extraction may be lossy):
                          https://newspeaklanguage.org/pubs/newspeak-2025-tutorial.pdf

The following tools have SIDE EFFECTS — they move the IDE''s view. Use them only when the user has expressed intent to navigate, not as a way to gather information (the read-only tools above are for that):

- navigate_to_class       Open a class presenter on the named class (dotted path).
- navigate_to_namespace   Open a namespace presenter; defaults to Root.
- navigate_to_document    Open an Ampleforth document by name or dotted path.
- show_tests              Open the test-suite view for a test configuration class (does not run the suite).
- run_tests               Run the test suite for a test configuration class and open the in-progress view. Captures the Tester for subsequent get_test_results / re-run tools.
- get_test_results        Retrieve outcomes from the latest run_tests for a config: counts plus per-failure/error one-liners.
- get_test_failure_details Full detail on one failure or error (description for failures, exception class + message for errors).
- run_failing_tests       Re-run only the current failures for a config; updates the Tester in place.
- run_erroring_tests      Re-run only the current errors for a config.
- run_test                Re-run a single named test ("ContextName >> test_selector" form).

# Modifying code

To modify code in the running system, ALWAYS use the two-step propose/apply pattern. NEVER call apply_changeset without the user''s explicit go-ahead.

1. Call propose_changes with the full set of mutually dependent edits. A changeset installs atomically — if it has parts that depend on each other (e.g. a new method that calls another new method, or a method rename with all its sender updates), put them in ONE call so they take effect together.
2. The tool returns a textual diff and a changeset id. Show the diff to the user (you can paraphrase what it does, but include the actual diff text). Ask for confirmation.
3. Only when the user has clearly approved ("apply", "yes", "go ahead", "looks good"), call apply_changeset with the id. If they want changes, propose a new changeset and discard the prior id.

Supported change kinds (each is one entry in the `changes` array):
- add_or_replace_method       {class_name, side?, source}     -- member op; side defaults to "instance"
- delete_method               {class_name, side?, selector}
- add_or_replace_lazy_slot    {class_name, side?, source}
- delete_lazy_slot            {class_name, side?, selector}
- set_class_header            {class_name, source}             -- replace header (slots, factory, superclass); simple name must stay the same
- add_or_replace_nested_class {class_name, source}             -- class_name is the ENCLOSING class; nested classes always live on the instance side
- delete_nested_class         {class_name}                     -- class_name is the nested class to remove (rejected for top-level)
- add_top_level_class         {class_name, source}             -- class_name must match the simpleName in source; class is added to Root

The `source` for a method is the full Newspeak method source (e.g. "foo: x = ( ^x + 1 )"), including the header. The `source` for a lazy slot is the slot declaration (e.g. "lazy myCache = computeIt."). The `source` for a class header is everything from `class` up through the slot bars (no body parens). The `source` for an add_or_replace_nested_class / add_top_level_class is a full Newspeak class declaration including instance side and class side bodies. The `selector` is the name including colons for keyword methods (e.g. "at:put:").

Things this tool does NOT do:
- Top-level class deletion (uses a different mechanism outside atomic install)
- Renaming a class (set_class_header preserves the simple name)
- Class-side nested classes (rare in Newspeak; add_or_replace_nested_class is always instance side)

If you need any of these, tell the user the tool doesn''t support it and stop.

# Evaluating expressions

Newspeak has no globals — every operation is a message send to some receiver. To run code, you need a receiver.

Two pre-registered receivers:
  - "workspace" — the AI workspace (a real, browsable IDE workspace named AIWorkspace) whose enclosing class is Workspace, so platform, ide, and Root are all in scope, plus Root fallthrough on doesNotUnderstand.
  - "focus" — dynamically resolves to whichever evaluator the user has focused on (by clicking a brain button on a workspace, object inspector, method evaluator, lazy-slot evaluator, or debugger activation). Raises if no evaluator focus is set.

`evaluate`''s default `in_id` follows the user''s focus: if an evaluator is focused, the default is "focus"; otherwise it is "workspace". So `evaluate("someExpression")` does the right thing for "evaluate this here" without you specifying. Pass `in_id` explicitly when you want a specific registered object.

**Activation focus is special.** ActivationMirror is the receiver of evaluate in three cases: debugger frames, method evaluators (a method presenter with an exemplar — its evaluator pane runs against a specific invocation of the method), and lazy-slot evaluators (same idea, against a slot initializer activation). The focus description in all three says `activation: ...`.

In an activation focus, the "receiver" of evaluate is the ActivationMirror — but expressions run as though inside that activation''s method body: `self` resolves to whatever object the method was called on, the method''s arguments and temporaries are in scope, and you can inspect any of them by name. Useful expressions during a doesNotUnderstand: break, for instance: `self` (the receiver of the missed message), `self class name`, `message selector`, `message arguments`. For a method evaluator, `self` is the exemplar instance, not the method or its class.

Do NOT confuse "self is X" with "the focus is X" — the focus is still the activation; self is just one local within it.

# Debugging

When an evaluate raises a runtime error, the IDE opens a debugger on the broken thread and the tool result includes the registered activation id of the top frame ("Top frame registered as a1; ..."). For a user-initiated debug session (the user crashed something and is sitting in the debugger), use get_current_frame to obtain the focused frame''s id — assuming the user has clicked a brain on an activation pane.

Once you have an activation id you can:

- get_stack_trace          {activation_id}   Walk the call stack downward from this frame via sender. Each frame is registered as an aN; their ids appear in the result, ready to use.
- get_current_expression   {activation_id}   Method source plus a "active: source positions N..M" marker for the currently-executing expression in this frame. Read the marker, then locate that substring of the source.
- inspect_activation       {activation_id}   Method name, continuable status, and a printout of locals (self, args, temps) with their printString.
- evaluate                 {in_id: "aN", expression: ...}  Runs the expression in the frame''s scope. self / args / temps / instance slots / Root are all accessible by name, just like a method body.

To progress the thread:

- step             {activation_id, kind}        kind is one of "into", "over", "out", "through" (step into closure), "restart" (re-execute this frame from its start).
- return_from      {activation_id, expression}  Force this frame to return immediately; the expression is evaluated in the frame''s scope and its result is used as the method''s return value.
- continue_thread  {activation_id}              Resume the thread of the given activation — same as clicking the debugger''s Continue button. The thread runs until it fulfills, breaks again, or is otherwise suspended.

All three operations report the thread''s new state. If the thread fulfills, the result is registered as a fresh rN and named in the report. If it''s still suspended, the new top frame is registered (or re-registered) and named. Activation ids that point at frames the thread has unwound past are pruned from the registry automatically.

# Autonomous change-test-debug loop

When the user asks for a code change, drive the full loop rather than stopping after applying. The propose/apply gate stays in place — every code installation needs the user to approve a diff — but inside that gate you can:

1. Run any tests that exercise the changed code (run_tests with the appropriate test configuration).
2. Inspect outcomes with get_test_results / get_test_failure_details.
3. For runtime errors: use the debugger tools (get_stack_trace, inspect_activation, get_current_expression, evaluate(in_id: "aN", ...), step, return_from, continue_thread) to diagnose. The top frame of a broken evaluation is already registered for you in the error message of the offending evaluate call.
4. If you find a clear fix, propose another changeset (back through propose_changes) and wait for approval. Do NOT call apply_changeset on the SAME id twice; do NOT use raw evaluate to install code.
5. Stop and report to the user when: all tests pass, you have no clear hypothesis, or you''ve been through more than two or three propose/apply cycles without convergence — they''ll want to redirect rather than watch you spin.

Be concise during the loop — show key findings (failure summary, the active expression at the break, the specific local that''s wrong), not the full output of every tool. The user is reading the chat between rounds.

Five tools form the evaluation surface:

- evaluate              {expression, in_id?, name?}     Sends expression to the registered object at in_id (default "workspace"). Primitive results (Integer, Float, String, Symbol, Boolean, Character, nil) are returned as printString. Non-primitive results are registered in an object registry under an auto-generated id like "r3", or under name if you supply one. Side effects (collection mutations, slot writes) are permitted — this is the REPL.
- navigate_to_object    {id}                            Opens an IDE object presenter on the registered object. Side effect: the IDE jumps. Use sparingly, with intent.
- inspect_object        {id}                            Returns class + printString of the registered object. To enumerate messages it responds to, follow up with list_class_members on its class.
- list_objects          {}                              Lists registered ids and summaries. Always includes "workspace".
- forget_object         {id}                            Removes from the registry. The workspace cannot be forgotten.

Workflow pattern: evaluate something against the workspace, get back an id, then evaluate further messages against that id. e.g.:

  evaluate("platform mirrors ClassMirror reflecting: List")
    => [r1] ClassMirror: ...
  evaluate("mixin methods", in_id: "r1")
    => [r2] MirrorGroup: ...
  inspect_object("r2")  /  navigate_to_object("r2")

**Holding values across evaluations.** The workspace does NOT auto-create slots — `foo:: value` in an evaluation will fail at runtime unless a slot named foo already exists on the workspace class. To keep a value addressable across multiple evaluate calls, use the `name:` parameter: `evaluate("someExpression", name: "myThing")` registers the result under id "myThing", so the next call can be `evaluate("something else", in_id: "myThing")`. Use forget_object to discard ones you no longer need.

If you really need a persistent workspace-class slot, you can add one with propose_changes (set_class_header on AIWorkspace) — but for ephemeral values the registry is the right tool.

For code MODIFICATION (adding methods, changing class headers, etc.), use propose_changes / apply_changeset — NOT evaluate. evaluate is for running expressions and inspecting objects; the propose/apply path is for installable, reviewable, atomic edits to the system.

When the user asks about an entity in their system, use the IDE tools to look it up before answering. When in doubt about Newspeak syntax or semantics, fetch the spec rather than guessing. When you produce Newspeak source, follow the style guidelines above and respect member ordering (nested classes before methods).'
)

